<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Asks Candidate Countries to Improve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Monday asked countries which are applying for EU membership to
improve their environmental protection standards.
</P>
<P>
EU Environment Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard said that the
candidate countries must prepare "tight and realistic" programs on
the environment.
</P>
<P>
A special council meeting attended by environment ministers
from all the candidate countries already in the accession talks
and the 15 member states was held in Brussels on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, according to Bjerregaard, was to bring home the
message to candidate countries that the environment issue might be
one of the obstacles hindering them in the screening phase.
</P>
<P>
Screening is part of the process before accession negotiations
which are scheduled to start on January 7 next year.
</P>
<P>
EU officials later explained that the environment programs to
be prepared by the candidate countries have to comply
legislatively, institutionally and physically with EU rules.
</P>
<P>
The EU has started accession talks with Poland, Hungary, the
Czech Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, Romania, Lithuania, Latvia and Slovakia are also
applying for EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
