<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Concerned over Weekend Violence in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The secretary-general of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) Monday expressed his
concern over the violence triggered by the murder of an opposition
politician in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Javier Solana called on all sides to show utmost restraint and
create conditions for the restoration of peace and stability in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that NATO was committed to promoting stability and
security in the Balkan country where the western military alliance
has been cooperating with the Albanian government through NATO's
Partnership for Peace programs.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, demonstrators shot their way into the office of
Socialist Prime Minister Fatos Nano and set the ground floor on
fire in protest against the murder of Azem Hajdari and his
bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
Hajdari was the leader of the opposition Democratic Party and
was killed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Albanian capital Tirana witnessed fresh
violence in which armed rioters shot at and bombed Nano's office
after Hajdari's funeral.
</P>
<P>
Rioters also reportedly seized tanks from the guards, and
surrounded national TV stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
