<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Conducts Tests of 'Arrow' Missile System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel successfully
conducted an integrated test of its "Arrow" missile system Monday
afternoon, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The test was conducted in a military base outside Tel Aviv and
it was the first time that all three components of the defense
system -- the missile, the radar and the fire-control system -- had
been involved, the radio quoted officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
An 'Arrow' missile did not carry out an actual interception in
the test, which lasted 97 seconds, but it traced and destroyed a
simulated target before blasting itself up as planned over the
sea, officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said the data of the simulated target were fed into the
radar and the fire-control system, which launched and guided the
missile to fly and then destroy the target. Every component of
the system operated very well, they added.
</P>
<P>
This was the sixth test of the 'Arrow' defense system, but the
first time all its components were tested, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the U.S., which helps fund the
anti-missile defense system, watched the test along with Israeli
military and aircraft industry officials, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The Arrow anti-missile system is designed to track incoming
missiles and guide an anti-missile missile at a speed of two miles
(nearly three kilometers) per second to within four meters of the
target.
</P>
<P>
Israel demanded several months ago that the U.S.-sponsored
program be expanded from two Arrow batteries to three. Officials
said more tests were planned and the system is expected to be
ready for initial deployment within two year, Israel Radio
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
