<HEADLINE> UK Considering to Call G7 Summit on World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain, the current
presidency of the Group of Seven (G7) industrial countries, said
Monday that its government is considering to call an emergency G7
summit to discuss the global economy.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters Monday that the
summit would take place only after a meeting of G7 finance
ministers in Washington on October 3.
</P>
<P>
"A meeting is not ruled out but it's not definite either. What
we want to do is take all the discussions that are going on and
draw conclusions as to whether a world economic summit would be
useful," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Another government source stressed that Russia's serious
economic and financial difficulties would be a major focus of this
emergency G7 summit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the senior government officials of the G7 countries
held a one-day meeting in London to discuss the worsening Russian
financial situation.
</P>
<P>
Russian deputy Foreign Minister Georgy Mamedov, who is in
London to brief G7 representative, said the London talks had been
"very successful economically and politically."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that G7 officials expressed the hope that new
Russian government would succeed as soon as possible in
stabilizing Russia's economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
