<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Stock Exchange Shows Increasing Activity in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus Stock Exchange
(CSE) has shown an increasing activity in many sectors in its
operation in 1997, CSE Chairman Dinos Papadopoulos said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the annual report for 1997, Papadopoulos said the
volume of transactions surpassed 170 million Cyprus pounds
(about 340 million U.S. dollars) and average daily volume was
around 700,000 pounds (about 1.4 million dollars) compared with
670,000 pounds (about 1.34 million dollars) the year before.
</P>
<P>
"The Cyprus Stock Exchange saw intense activity in 1997 and
achieved its initial goals as planned. We are now moving on
to fully computerize the stock exchange, hopefully by the end
of September, and attract new companies, local and foreign, as
well as foreign investors," Papadopoulos told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
However, Papadopoulos pointed out it would be unrealistic to
expect miracles because of the small size of the Cypriot
economy.
</P>
<P>
Referring to tax incentives offered to trading companies,
Papadopoulos said newcomers have reduced tax rates, offshore
companies can invest in the stock exchange without losing
their offshore status and any profit they make through the
exchange is not taxable.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on developments in 1998, he said the general
price index shows a 14 percent increase since the beginning of
the year with an average daily volume of transactions of about
1.33 million pounds (2.33 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The CSE was lunched in March 1996 after years of operating in
an unofficial capacity under the auspices of the Cyprus Chamber
of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
It has now 57 listed companies with a market capitalization
of about 1.3 billion Cyprus pounds (about 2.6 billion dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
