<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges Security Council to Probe UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq demanded once
again on Monday that the Security Council of the United Nations
initiate a serious investigation of the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Security Council, Iraq's Deputy Prime
Minister Tareq Aziz said initiating a probe may correct the
situation within UNSCOM and make it to be an impartial
international body.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has complained that UNSCOM is controlled by the United
States and it is the United States which decides on the
Commission's agenda and even on its working methods.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said were the UNSCOM a neutral and impartial international
body, it would have informed the Security Council long ago that
its task under Resolution 687 of 1991 had been completed.
</P>
<P>
The International Atomic Energy Agency has long since completed
its task under the resolution and the Council should close the
files in this area, but this has not happened because the UNSCOM
entrusted with the technical implementation of the Council's
resolution is neither neutral nor impartial, and because of the
United States of America exercises arbitrary power within the
Council and is preventing it from recognizing the facts, Aziz
said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on August 5 announced to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM
until it gets restructured. Security Council on August 6 called
Iraq's decision totally unacceptable and urged it to reverse its
decision, but Iraq reiterated not to change its position. The
Council last week adopted a resolution which decided to suspend
the regular review of sanctions against Iraq until it resumes full
cooperation with UNSCOM.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
