<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Primakov to Take Bold Steps in Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Monday urged Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to
take bold steps in economic reforms, and warned against a return
to the Soviet Union era.
</P>
<P>
"He (Primakov) and President Yeltsin face one of the great
challenges of their time," Clinton said in a speech at the Council
on Foreign Relations in New York.
</P>
<P>
"Never has there been a more important moment to set a clear
direction for the future, to affirm the commitment of Russia to
democracy and to free markets, and to take decisive steps to
stabilize the economy and restore investor confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But if Russia is willing to take these steps, we must do
everything we can to provide support to them, because again I say
as long as ordinary people don't feel any benefits from this, in
the end it's going to be difficult to sustain the direction we
think the world should take," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton warned Primakov's new government against abandoning
market-opening reforms, saying U.S. economic support was at stake.
</P>
<P>
Some in Russia now talk of "abandoning the path of reform and
returning to policies of the past, even policies that have already
failed," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"At worst, adversity in Russia could affect not only the
Russian economy and prospects for our economic cooperation -- at
worst, it could have an impact on our cooperation with Russia on
nuclear disarmament; on fighting terrorism and the spread of
weapons of mass destruction; on standing together for peace, from
the Balkans to the Middle East," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
