<HEADLINE> Cabinda Issue, Angola's Internal Affairs: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Cabinda issue is Angola's
internal affairs and it should be solved through candid and open
dialogue, a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Santana Andre Pitra, Angola's Interior Minister made the
remarks here Sunday after attending the talks between the
governors of Angola's Cabinda province and the neighboring Congo
(B)'s Kouilou regional administrator, the Journal of Angola
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pitra made it clear at the talks that the Cabinda issue should
be solved on a negotiating table, not through arms.
</P>
<P>
Cabinda enclave on the Atlantic is sandwiched between Congo
(Brazzaville) and Congo (Kinshasa). Some organizations in the
enclave have been engaging in long years of armed struggle for
independence.
</P>
<P>
Pitra said Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos has met
his Congolese (B) counterpart Denis Sassou Nguesso over the
issue, and has agreed that neither should allow rebels on its
land to carry out armed activities against the other's
government.
</P>
<P>
The minister also demanded local government tighten its
security measures for security and stability, saying that "we
need stability to guarantee the free flow of personnel and goods,
and the ties of culture, sports and trade between the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
Alexander Honore Kapa, the Congolese (B) administrator vowed
to spare no pains to safeguard safety and cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Cabinda is rich in oil reserve, producing about 53 percent of
the total oil in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The biggest opposition, the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) has formed alliance with Cabinda
Enclave Liberation Front and the Union for the Liberation of
Cabinda, two major oppositions in Cabinda. These forces often
conduct armed harassments in Cabinda through neighboring
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
