<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Enforce Environmental Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government will
soon enforce a law on response, compensation and liability for
environmental damages to enhance the protection of deteriorating
environment in the country.
</P>
<P>
Raphael Adewoye, Director General and Chief Executive of the
Federal Environmental Protection Agency (FEPA), made the remarks
at the 10th conference of directors and general managers of state
environmental protection agencies which held in Lafia, Central
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported Monday that Adewoye
told the meeting that the law was aimed at putting in place a
legal framework capable of delivering a compasation formula
acceptable to all stake-holders in the interest of the damaged
environment.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the meeting urged the state
environmental protection agencies (SEPA) to submit their draft
policy framework on their relationship to FEPA.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the framework was necessary for a harmonized
and integrated approach that will help implement the proposed
national action program for combating soil erosion,
desertification and bush-burning in the country.
</P>
<P>
The communique also advised SEPAs to start the generation of
data on air quality and report to FEPA on regular basis and to
operate under the office of the state chief executives.
</P>
<P>
The conference recommended a phase privatization of solid
waste management in Nigeria to halt the nation's fragile
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
