<HEADLINE> African Swine Fever Breaks out in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
confirmed the outbreak of African swine fever in the country
which is said to be capable of wiping out entire pig population.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of the disease was first reported in Lagos and
Ogun states a few weeks ago and officials of Nigerian Agriculture
Ministry confirmed Sunday that there had been outbreaks in
Kaduna, Benue and Osun states.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ministry in capital Abuja said that
the disease is now spreading fast in the West African country,
warning that meat of affected pigs is not good for human
consumption, The Guardian reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no known cure of infected pigs nor vaccine available
to protect surviving animals through vaccination," it said,
adding that the only method of control is to enforce "very strict
movement of pigs and pig products".
</P>
<P>
Usually, the virulent disease leads to high mortality rate of
between 80 and 100 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
