<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen on Monday described as "a threat" the recent launch
of a satellite by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
and said the United State would be working closely with Japan to
meet the "threat".
</P>
<P>
The United States and Japan have charged that the DPRK tested
a new Taepo Dong 1 medium range missile over the Japanese
Mainland on August 31, although Pyongyang already refuted the
allegation and said what it launched was a satellite.
</P>
<P>
At a photo session with visiting members of the Japanese
Diet, Cohen said the United States and Japan "have been
disturbed by the recent test on the part of the North Koreans."
</P>
<P>
"Any threat to Japan's security is also a threat to America,
so we intend to work very closely with our strong allies in
dealing with this particular issue," Cohen told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, State Department officials said U.S., Japanese and
South Korean officials were meeting there on Monday to discuss
security in the western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Both the United States and Japan could "cooperate
on theater missile defense issues, exchange information and
perhaps cooperate in other ways."
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to continue this very strong relationship
we have with Japan and deal with security issues that affect
us," he said. 
</P>
