<HEADLINE> Air Canada Pilots End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Pilots at Air Canada voted
overwhelmingly in favor of accepting a new contract, ending a 13-day
strike at Canada's largest airline.
</P>
<P>
"Air Canada is back in business with more than 150 flights
scheduled to operate today," the airline announced in a statement
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Beginning at 13:00 EDT, the airline began phasing in
approximately one quarter of its normal operations to serve
primarily domestic and transborder destinations from its hubs across
Canada," it said.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada said its full daily schedule of 650 flights will be
phased in over the next four days.
</P>
<P>
Over 83 percent of the pilots who cast their ballots voted in
favor of the new contract, and about 94 percent of the 2,100 pilots
cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
"Accordingly, the Air Canada Pilots Association has announced
that the strike is over," the pilots said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The strike began on September 1 when talks on a new pilots'
contract broke down over differences of wage increases and working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The pilots asked for 12 percent wage hikes over the next two
years, and the airline offered nine percent.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the new contract offered the same wage
provisions as the airline's last offer, but had improvements in
other areas such as benefits.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't go on strike for nothing," Jean-Marc Belanger,
spokesman of the pilots association, told a news briefing. "We have
achieved a lot more than at the beginning of the strike."
</P>
<P>
The strike has stranded thousands of Air Canada passengers. And it
is estimated that the airline lost up to 130 million U.S. dollars as
the result of the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
