<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Action on World Economic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Monday called on world economic powers "to act together to spur
global economy" as the world is facing "the biggest Challenge
in a half century".
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Council on Foreign Relations in New York,
Clinton said the United States has an "inescapable obligation" to
help resolve the economic crisis affecting a growing number of
countries.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the fact that 30 percent of the U.S. economic
growth has been made due to trade with overseas countries since he
became president in 1992, Clinton said this is why "ordinary
Americans should care if Asia or Russia or South America are on
solid footing."
</P>
<P>
"These peoples are our customers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the world's second largest economy, should remain a key
to resolving the economic crisis, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Besides appealing to Congress to provide funds to the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), the president is asking
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan to meet with their counterparts in other countries in
the next 30 days to deal with the current economic issues.
</P>
<P>
"Above all we must accelerate our efforts to reform the
international financial system," Clinton said, hoping that the
meeting "will recommend ways to adapt the international financial
architecture to the 21st century". 
</P>
</TEXT>
