<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Surge with Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The filling of Russia's
political vacuum and a continuing rally on Wall Street fired
European markets with buying enthusiasm Monday.
</P>
<P>
Leading London shares surged on a diet of fresh takeover news,
corporate results and a strong Wall Street showing. The FTSE 100
closed up 150 points or almost 3 percent to 5,269.
</P>
<P>
Football stocks were once again in demand as takeover fever
gripped the sector. Earlier, another set of benign producer prices
figures had little impact on gilts or equities. In addition,
domestic corporate news included a stock-swap agreement between
Hardy Oil &AMP; Gas and British-Borneo and a possible merger between
the land-based defense units of GKN and Alvis.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares traded higher with investors
encouraged by Wall Street's upswing, a stronger dollar and the
re-election in Bavaria Sunday of a conservative government. The
leading Dax index closed up 159 points at 4,896.5.
</P>
<P>
The rally was "a sum of many parts," according to a
Frankfurt-based portfolio manager. "It's partly technical, partly
the result of good news."
</P>
<P>
The dollar's gains against the Dmark also brought investors
back to the bourse. The dollar hit a 16-month low last Thursday,
triggering a flight from Germany's dollar-sensitive, export-driven
stocks.
</P>
<P>
While German share prices were up across the board, the bank
sector posted steady gains. Traders said the banks are retracing
earlier losses due to the Russian crisis.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks finished higher too with investor
confidence returning on New York's strong performance. The leading
Cac-40 index closed up 136 points at 3,715.
</P>
<P>
But traders said the rally appears stronger than it actually is
because of very low volumes.
</P>
<P>
"The rebound is in fact rather timid," a trader at ABN Amro
said. "There are plenty of buyers around but a near absence of
sellers."
</P>
<P>
After a disastrous market performance last week, French banking
shares were charging ahead.
</P>
<P>
But traders said the rally doesn't come close to countering the
heavy losses banking shares experienced last week on market fears
of heavy losses in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The banks are gaining some ground, yes, but it's nothing
compared to what they lost last week," the trader said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
