<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Release of Senior S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The ruling African
National Congress (ANC) Monday welcomed Mozambique's decision to
release Robert McBride, a suspended director of South African
Foreign Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, ANC spokesman Thabo Masebe also thanked
Mcbride for cooperating with the Mozambican authorities in their
investigations of gun-running allegations against him.
</P>
<P>
"We trust that he will continue to cooperate until the
judicial process is completed," said Masebe.
</P>
<P>
McBride was set free Monday. His release was initially planned
for last Friday, but his South African lawyer, Jose nascimento,
was quoted as saying his release could not go through last week
because of bureaucratic hitches.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent reference to criticism that the ANC did nothing
to help secure McBride's release, he said the ANC respected the
sovereignty of Mozambique, and that it was committed to the rule
of law and the judicial process.
</P>
<P>
McBride was in charge of Asian affairs before his arrest. He
was arrested in March in a Mozambican town bordering with South
Africa. He was charged of gun-smuggling.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Mozambican security authorities also
tried to bring charges of spying against McBride, but nothing
more has been heard about this. 
</P>
</TEXT>
