<HEADLINE> U.S. Commerce Secretary Visits S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Commerce Secretary of
the United States William Daley arrived in Pretoria Monday,
kicking off his two-day visit to South Africa, the U.S. embassy
said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Daley said he was expecting to meet South
African business and government leaders to discuss ways of
strengthening commercial relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"In particular, I am looking forward to meeting my South
African counterpart, Minister of Trade and Industry Alec Erwin,
and to joining him and several of his colleagues in SADC to
discuss regional economic issues."
</P>
<P>
SADC stands for the Southern African Development Community,
which consists of 14 countries.
</P>
<P>
Daley, who last visited South Africa in March with President
Bill Clinton, said he would return again in December with a major
business delegation which would also travel to Angola, Kenya and
Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
"This trade mission will build on President Clinton's
commitment to enhancing U.S. commercial engagements with Africa
by developing a genuine partnership for trade and investment,"
Daley said.
</P>
<P>
Daley is due to leave South Africa Wednesday morning for
Tanzania and Kenya, where he will examine how the American
government can help victims of of last month's twin U.S. embassy
bombings -- in Nairobi and Dar Es Salaam -- that killed more than
260 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
