<HEADLINE> Growing Buyer Attendance Recorded at HK Watch Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The world's largest
timepiece event, the just closed Hong Kong Watch and Clock Fair
'98, attracted a total of 15,818 buyers from all over the world,
up 15 percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The growth in buyer attendance further strengthened Hong
Kong's position as the major supplier and distribution hub of
watches and clocks in Asia," said C.S. Lee, director of
exhibitions of the Hong Kong Trade Development Council (HKTDC)
which was co-organizer of the fair.
</P>
<P>
The number of overseas buyers attending this year's event was
5,692, up 6 percent over 1997, with visitors from Asia topping the
list, according to German-based independent audit specialists,
the Voluntary Control of Fair and Exhibition Statistics (FKM).
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Watch and Clock Fair was co-organized by the
HKTDC, the Hong Kong Watch Manufacturers Association and the
Federation of Hong Kong Watch Trades and Industries. This year a
total of 811 exhibitors from 15 countries and regions displayed
their latest timepiece products.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland has now become the top source of buyers,
followed by Japan and Taiwan. Eight Asian countries and regions
are among the top 10 of overseas buyer attendance, reaffirming the
fair as Asia's preeminent timepiece event, said Lee.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's other traditional markets such as the United States
and Western Europe have also demonstrated positive growth, from 5
percent for the U.S. to 55 percent for the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
