<HEADLINE> Hong Kong University Set to Create Digital Campus for Networked World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,300 first-year
students of Hong Kong University were presented with IBM ThinkPad
notebook computers here on Tuesday, as the first step of the
university's ambitious Information Technology (IT) Campaign to
create a "digital campus".
</P>
<P>
The move, supported by the IBM China/Hong Kong Limited, will
provide the university's all students and staff with access to
computing power, network tools and resources from anywhere, on or
off campus. And this would make the university at the forefront
regionally in the application of IT to pedagogy.
</P>
<P>
The students were offered substantial incentives to purchase
one of the three different features of notebooks, all equipped
with a 233 MHz processor and, amongst other features, a built-in
CD-ROM drive. By using their own ThinkPads, students will be able
to access the Internet as well as the university's own network via
some 10,000 network access points located throughout the campus.
</P>
</TEXT>
