<HEADLINE> Franchise of Years-old HK Ferry Company To Expire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong government
announced Tuesday that the franchise granted to the Hongkong and
Yaumati Ferry Company (HYF), due to expire on March 31, 1999, will
not be extended.
</P>
<P>
The ferry company, with a history of 75 years, now operates six
 outlying islands services and six inner harbor and new town
routes.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive-in-Council has decided that the HYF routes,
 together with the Central to Hung Hom service operated by the
Star Ferry Company, should be grouped into different packages for
public tender. A license is normally granted for a period of three
years.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision of the Chief Executive-in-Council, a
government spokesman said: "Our immediate priority is to ensure
continuity of ferry services, in particular the services to the
outlying islands which have no land transport alternatives should
be maintained and further improved after HYF's current franchise
expires."
</P>
<P>
A gazette notice inviting tender submissions on six outlying
islands routes, grouped into three packages, will be published on
Friday, with tender closing on October 12. HYF and other operators
would be free to put in their bids.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18 companies, including HYF, have expressed an
interest in operating ferry services in Hong Kong, the spokesman
revealed.
</P>
<P>
A separate public tender for the inner harbor and new town
routes will be conducted shortly afterwards, said the spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges Israel to Work for Comprehensive Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri Tuesday called upon the Israeli government and people
to work for materializing comprehensive peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu should take an
affirmative stance towards the peace process. Because peace serves
the interest of Israel in the first instance, and also the
interest of all the countries in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian prime minister made the remarks while addressing
an international economic conference organized by Euromoney, an
international financial foundation, which opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The get-together is held under the title: "Promising Economies
of the Arab World -- Gold Coasts for Invest."
</P>
<P>
He told the gathering that the Middle East peace process has
been in a standstill over the past two years since Netanyahu
assumed office in Israel in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri called on Netanyahu to take a positive attitude on the
peace process, stop rejecting initiatives aimed at propelling the
process and respect the relevant U.N. Security Council
resolutions, agreements already signed with the Palestinian sides
and the basic terms of reference agreed upon for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have been stalled since
Israel began building settlements in Arab East Jerusalem in March
1997. U.S. mediation attempts have been frustrated by Netanyahu's
rejection of a 13 percent further Israeli redeployment plan.
</P>
<P>
Along with Arab ministers, more than 700 economists, investors,
bankers, brokers, representing 25 Arab and other countries, are
participating in the three-day conference.
</P>
<P>
The opening session was attended by Egyptian ministers, senior
bank officials, and chairmen of leading companies and
corporations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
