<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aspirin May Prevent Colon Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A new research by U.S.
and German scientists suggested that aspirin may significantly
suppress genetic mutations that lead to some type of colon cancer, the
Washington Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some previous studies had suggested that aspirin might help
prevent colon cancer, but nobody knew why it would work.
</P>
<P>
Now a team of U.S. and German researchers has examined a
severe, inherited type of colon cancer and found that in test
tubes, aspirin suppressed the genetic mutations that cause some
tumors. They said aspirin essentially pushed genetically unstable
cells to commit cellular suicide instead of reproducing.
</P>
<P>
lead researcher Richard Fishel of Thomas Jefferson University
in Philadelphia and colleagues at Germany's University of
Regensborg, reached the above conclusion after studying
hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer. In the United States
about 20,000 people have been struck by this cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
