<HEADLINE> UK Cracks down on Internet Racism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- British Home Secretary Jack
Straw on Tuesday announced that Britain would crack down on racism
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Board of Deputies of British Jews, Straw said
the National Criminal Intelligence Service (NCIS) would play an
important role against threatening, abusive and racist material
published on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet offers exciting opportunities for global
communication, but it is vulnerable to abuse, because Websites and
newsgroups are accessible from across international borders," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for governments across the world to work
together to remove illegal Websites and prosecute those
responsible.
</P>
<P>
An expert in the subject has warned that groups were not only
using the Internet for racism publicity but also for planning
terrorist activity.
</P>
<P>
Racism was identified in a report compiled by the NCIS early
this year as one of the principal areas in which the Internet was
abused.
</P>
<P>
The NCIS has already been cooperating with other police
agencies around the world to target child pornography rings, and
intelligence reports suggest that similar co-operation will be
required to combat racism.
</P>
<P>
Net experts agree that the majority of right wing, neo-Nazi and
fascist Websites that publish racist material are concentrated in
North America, Germany and Scandinavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
