<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Edge Up 0.2 Pct in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. retail sales rose
0.2 percent in August as compared with a 0.6 percent decline in
July caused mainly by a General Motors strike that had sharply cut
auto sales, the Commerce Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
August sales increased to a seasonally adjusted 224.8 billion
U.S. dollars, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
However, except the automobile category, sales of all other
retail goods rose by a relatively modest 0.3 percent in August.
That followed a 0.6 percent jump in July, better than first
reported.
</P>
<P>
Plentiful jobs and rising incomes have spurred consumer
spending in 1998. Moreover, unusually good mortgage rates have
encouraged Americans to buy houses, spurring sales of furniture
and home improvement supplies.
</P>
<P>
In August, sales of durable goods, items expected to last three
years or more, were unchanged after dropping 2.1 percent in July
due to the nearly-two-month-long GM strikes.
</P>
<P>
Furniture stores reported a strong 1.0 percent sale growth in
August, after similar jumps in the previous three months.
</P>
<P>
But sales at hardware and building supply stores dropped 0.5
percent. Auto dealers reported another 0.2 percent business drop
on top of the sharp slippery they suffered during the GM strikes.
</P>
<P>
Sales of nondurable goods were up 0.3 percent in August in the
wake of a 0.6 percent increase in the previous month. Sales at
clothing and accessory shops were up 1.2 percent and department
store sales rose 0.3 percent as back-to-school shopping got
underway.
</P>
<P>
Food store sales were up 0.4 percent. Business at bars and
restaurants fell 0.2 percent in August. Drug store sales rose 1.1
percent, but continuing low fuel prices brought down sales by
another 0.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
