<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drug To Treat Depression With Less Side Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists said that
they have developed a new drug called MK-869 which blocks a
brain chemical "substance P", thus being highly effective at
alleviating depression while causing fewer side effects than
existing medications.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Washington Post, in a
preliminary study, Mark S. Kramer of Merck Research Laboratories
in West Point, Pennsylvania State, and colleagues studied 213
patients with moderate to severe depression who took the new
drug MK-869, the anti-depressant Paxil or a placebo. Six weeks
later MK-869 reduced depression as effectively as Paxil, but
those taking MK-869 were much less likely to report side
effects, particularly sexual dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
"Substance P" is a little-understood chemical messenger
concentrated in parts of the brain involved in emotion. The
researchers said that MK-869's effectiveness could provide new
insights into the chemical's function, and possibly the
underlying cause of depression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
