<HEADLINE> Jiang, Li Write Inscriptions for Ambitious New University (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin and
National People's Congress (NPC) Stadning Committee Chairman Li
Peng have both written inscriptions for the founding of China's
largest university, the new Zhejiang University.
</P>
<P>
The new mega-university, founded today, consists of the former
Zhejiang University, Hangzhou University, Zhejiang Agricultural
University and Zhejiang University of Medical Sciences, all based
in this capital of east China's Zhejiang Province. It aims to be
one of the world's first-class universities in next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's inscription reads, "Run Zhejiang University well
and contribute still more to rejuvenating the country through
science and education", while Li's goes, "Carry forward the fine
school traditions and train talented people for building the
country."
</P>
<P>
The new Zhejiang University now tops all Chinese universities
in terms of academic departments, majors, number of students,
faculty and staff, campus area and computer network. It has 11
branches of learning, 145 four-year majors, 12 post-doctorate
programs, and 124 doctorate specialities as well as 192 master's
degree majors.
</P>
<P>
The new university has some 30,000 students, including 3,500
post-graduates and over 1,500 doctoral candidates. It has more
than 10,000 faculty members, including more than 800 professors,
1,600 associate professors, seven academicians of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and six academicians of the Chinese Academy of
Engineering.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing attended today's inauguration
ceremony. He said that the founding of the new university
represents another step China has taken to reform its system of
higher learning and will certainly promote the rational
utilization of educational resources in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang, Li Write Inscriptions for Ambitious New University (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Modeled after those of the former Soviet Union, Chinese
colleges and universities founded during the 1950s and 1960s were
all run by the state, State Council departments, industries, or
provinces or regions. This led to a surfeit of specialized
colleges, a waste of resources and low efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The new Zhejiang University's president, Pan Yunhe, a member of
the Chinese Academy of Engineering and a computer expert, said
that the university will emphasize on research and encourage
creativity to make breakthroughs in major fields. He pledged to
bring the total number of graduate students in the university to
over 10,000 by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
"The new university will focus on establishing new disciplines,
especially in the frontier sciences, so as to enhance its
competitiveness," Pan added.
</P>
<P>
The new university, which consists of five campuses with a
total area of approximately 287 ha with 1.7 million sq m of
building space, is expected to get a total of 800 million yuan
(96.6 million US dollars) in funding from the central treasury and
the provincial government, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The university's higher education computer network, the largest
of its kind in China, offers long-distance information on
teaching, academic research, scientific programs and school
administration.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, faculty staff and students will be able to conduct
scientific cooperation through the network or consult its
electronic library, as well as conduct academic exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
