<HEADLINE> Egypt Profits From Financial Crises Elsewhere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Egypt's Banks Union
Mahmoud Abdel Aziz said Tuesday local banks have made money out of
the financial crises in Asia and Russia, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Aziz, speaking on the sidelines of a conference organized
by Euromoney Organization for the rising markets in the Arab
countries here, said that the crisis in South East Asia has
affected the market by about 3 percent while the crisis in Russia
had a lesser impact because of the powerful indicators in the
Egyptian economy.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank of Egypt (NBE) made use of the crises and
purchased crumbling shares in the world market, selling it later
at a higher price making a profit of about two to three million
dollars on stocks in the Asian market and about two million
dollars on stocks in the Russian market, according to Abdel Aziz,
who is also NBE chairman.
</P>
<P>
NBE also bought 1.4 billion dollars worth of securities in the
London stock exchange during the crisis and earned some 100
million dollars while the Commercial International Bank (CIB)
bought some 25 million dollars worth of shares and made profits of
about 5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The NBE, one of Egypt's four largest state-run banks, is now
concentrating its activities on foreign deals.
</P>
<P>
It has purchased a foreign bank in the U.S. which became a NBE
branch that will serve North and South America and is considering
establishing branches in Montreal, Los Angeles and Argentine. It
is also studying prospects for opening small NBE branches in China.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Aziz also said that the NBE has the largest securities
portfolio in Egypt and is speculating with about 3 billion
Egypt pounds (882.4 million dollars) and makes daily deals in
about 5 million pounds (1.47 million dollars) to breathe life
in the capital market.
</P>
<P>
He said the Egyptian government was determined to proceed with
privatization and continue its march towards a free market economy
and open the doors to world markets along with injecting new
capitals to increase the stock market and banks activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
