<HEADLINE> Malaysia Condemns Killing of Iranian Diplomats in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday
condemned the killing of Iranian diplomats in Mazar al-Sharif in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia holds the Taliban authorities responsible for events
leading to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi in a statement
described the killing as the most despicable crime which was
contrary to all Islamic values and international law.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia calls on the Taliban authorities to fully account for
the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to bring to justice
all those responsible for the crime," Abdullah said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban authorities must now take all due measures to
ensure the safe return of all other remaining Iranian diplomats
and nationals in Afghanistan and to prevent the recurrence of such
incidents, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Malaysia also expressed its deep concern over the
deteriorating situation in Afghanistan and its implication to the
stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
He urged all parties concerned to exercise maximum restraint
and desist from any action that could further escalate the
situation.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia's solidarity with the people of Afghanistan as a
whole remains unchanged and is not aligned to any particular
faction," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, Malaysia has consistently urged all Afghan factions
to negotiate rather than prolong the fighting and continues to
urge all parties concerned to fully support the efforts of the UN
Special Envoy to search for a lasting political settlement," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also conveyed the Malaysian government's
condolence to the bereaved families and to the Iranian government
on the loss of the innocent lives.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that six Iranian diplomats and a journalist
were among nine killed when the Taliban militia seized the
northern Afghan city on August 8. 
</P>
