<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Rules Out Devaluation of Rupee Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Commerce Minister
Ishaq Dar Tuesday ruled out any devaluation of the Pakistani rupee
against the U.S. dollar and warned of stern action against
speculators and violators of rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
"We should curb the rumors about rupee devaluation and must try
to stabilize the local currency," he said at a press briefing
here.
</P>
<P>
Dar cited a number of decisions taken by the government
recently to check the speculative moves against the rupee and said
they have started producing positive results.
</P>
<P>
During the last 10 days, the rupee has gained around seven
rupees against the greenback and according to money changers, the
dollar closed at 56.10 and 56.50 rupees for spot buying and
selling on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister dispelled rumors that the rupee will be devalued
after negotiations with the team of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) currently visiting Pakistan to discuss its financial
package for the country.
</P>
<P>
Dar made it clear that there will not be any devaluation of the
rupee even if asked by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
"We will not accept any IMF conditionality which is against the
economic and financial interest of Pakistan," he said, adding it
is neither required or indicated by the economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
The only problem is on the balance of payment side which is
also "engineered," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said government officials will monitor the curb market to
ensure that rules and regulations, as set by the state bank, are
being adhered to.
</P>
<P>
The government will make sincere efforts to narrow the gap
between the composite rate and the official rate, said Dar.
</P>
<P>
The minister pledged to take strict actions against the
practice of over- and under-invoicing and those money changers who
attempt to speculate on devaluation of the rupee.
</P>
<P>
Dar disclosed that even some banks were found to be involved in
"irregular" practices. "We are going to implement regulations
meant for banks and money changers both licensed and un-licensed,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
