<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Ruble Tumbles After Brief Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Russian ruble slid to
12.2 to the U.S. dollar after rallying briefly on Tuesday in
electronic lot trading on the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange.
</P>
<P>
By 16:00 local time (12:00 GMT), quotes for deals ready for
delivery on Thursday stood at 10 to 13 rubles to the dollar, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the ruble had traded at 8.5 to 8.7 to the
dollar at the MICEX, up from Friday's 11.5 to 12 rubles.
</P>
<P>
Exchange points in Moscow are buying the dollar at the rate of
10 rubles, up from Monday's eight to nine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Viktor Gerashchenko, the newly appointed director
of the Central Bank, told deputies in the State Duma Tuesday that
the country could not cope without printing more money.
</P>
<P>
"There is a catastrophic shortage of money in Russia, many
commercial banks are in a difficult position," Gerashchenko said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said such a move would be taken only after
the new board of directors of the central bank was formed.
</P>
<P>
Gerashchenko said that President Boris Yeltsin had given oral
consent to the nominations of eight nominees to the board of
directors and ordered his chief of staff Valentin Yumashev to
prepare a letter introducing them to the State Duma (lower house
of parliament) for approval.
</P>
<P>
While Gerashchenko urged a speedy confirmation of the
candidates, the State Duma is not expected to approve the
nominations soon.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Zhukov, chairman of the Duma Budget Committee, told
his committee that the People's Power and Liberal Democratic
factions had objected to debating the nominations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Not forming the Central Bank of Russia's board of directors
is similar to not appointing a prime minister on time,"
Gerashchenko warned.
</P>
<P>
He said that the money-printing problem would be discussed
when the government and the central bank discussed policies for
the fourth quarter of the year and at talks with the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Many fear that printing more money would throw Russia into
hyperinflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
