<HEADLINE> Sky Chief Slams Nakata Rumour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- British Sky Sports chief Vic
Wakeling has branded stories claiming that his company had gone
behind Alex Ferguson's back to attempt to sign Hidetoshi Nakata
as "fanciful".
</P>
<P>
According to The Mirror newspaper on Tuesday, an official of
Rupert Murdoch's media empire was thought to have made a 6.25
million pounds bid for Nakata last week.
</P>
<P>
But the television boss made it clear that this was not the
case.
</P>
<P>
Wakeling said: "This story is completely untrue. During the
last week there there has been a lot of speculation.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of it has been mischievous and some of it downright
fanciful. This story falls into that second category."
</P>
<P>
Nakata, who dyed his hair orange during the World Cup, joined
Italian club Perugia and netted two goals in a sensational Serie
A debut against Juventus at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
A Perugia source was quoted in the Mirror saying: "At no time
during these negotiations was Ferguson's name touched upon,
despite the fact it was clearly on behalf of Manchester United."
</P>
</TEXT>
