<HEADLINE> IOC to Promote Sports Between Seoul, Pyongyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) will send a special envoy to the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) next week to initiate sports
programs between Seoul and Pyongyang, said IOC President Juan
Antonio Samaranch in Seoul on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch, who is in Seoul to chair the meeting of IOC's
executive board, said senior IOC official Thomas Bach will visit
Pyongyang to discuss the inter-Korean sports exchange programs
with DPRK officials.
</P>
<P>
Bach, an IOC Executive Board member from Germany, said he would
take a van donated by Daimler Benz Group as a present for the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Bach's visit will provide a good occasion to seek a
dialogue with North Korea's authorities on the IOC's proposal of
promoting inter-Korean sports activities," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Samaranch on Monday briefed President Kim
Dae-jung during a meeting at the presidential palace Chong Wa Dae.
</P>
<P>
Drug abuse was at the top of the agenda in the IOC executive
board meeting and Samaranch pledged the IOC's total commitment to
the fight against athletes' drug abuses.
</P>
<P>
The IOC could no longer tolerate athletes who cheated and lied
about drug scandals and would do everything possible to eradicate
the use of drugs among athletes, Samaranch said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
