<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Planning for Second Board Securities Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Emerging firms in China's
interior area will have chances to list and raise funds in Hong
Kong, as the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong is planning to set up a
second board market, an exchange official said here today.
</P>
<P>
No specific restrictions will be imposed on the kinds of
enterprises to be listed on the second board market and all
emerging enterprises, whether state-owned or private, have equal
chances for listing, Peng Ruchuan, executive director of the China
Development Division of the exchange, told an international
symposium.
</P>
<P>
A second board market is a securities trading market for
companies, especially emerging enterprises, that are not qualified
for listing on the main, and more standard, first board market. It
therefore gives the said companies a channel through which to
raise funds from the public, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The NASDAQ of the United States is a typical second board
market.
</P>
<P>
Currently, enterprises in interior China, mainly large
state-owned firms, raise funds in Hong Kong through issuing H
shares. To date, inland companies have raised more than 10 billion
US dollars through share issues in Hong Kong, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
Peng said that supervision over firms listed on the second
board market will be the same as over those listed on the main
market, though listing on the second board market need not be
approved by an official committee of listed firms.
</P>
<P>
The difference between the two markets is that the investment
risk at the second board market is even greater, and the amount of
funds raised at the second board market is relatively smaller,
according to Peng.
</P>
<P>
He said that, personally, he is fully confident about the
prospects of the second board market, which has the full backing
of the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, France Move Ahead With Peace Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and France have reached a
plan of action to set in motion their joint initiative to rescue
the faltering Middle East peace process, Egypt's Ambassador to
France Ali Maher said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The plan was formulated by a working group of experts from both
governments in Paris Monday, he told the Egyptian radio Voice of
Arabs over the phone.
</P>
<P>
"The prevalent idea is to hold an international conference to
rescue peace in two phases. The first will include nations not
directly involved in negotiations and the second will involve all
the parties concerned," Maher said.
</P>
<P>
"The conference is to draw world attention to the threat of a
continued peace impasse to regional and global security," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-French group began meetings in Paris Monday to
press ahead the initiative launched by their presidents last May.
</P>
<P>
The conference as described by officials in May would take
place in two steps, starting with a larger conference, then a
smaller one including nations like Israel directly concerned with
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa paid a
visit to France to discuss with President Jacques Chirac how to
organize the new conference.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. attempts to break the peace deadlock between the
Palestinians and Israelis have been frustrated by Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's refusal to accept a U.S. peace plan
calling for Israel to pullback troops from a further 13.1 percent
of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations have languished for 18 months
since the Israeli government began building Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem in March 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
