<HEADLINE> Xi'an Experiments with Natural Gas-Powered Buses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- This capital of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, has started running buses powered by
natural gas on a certain route.
</P>
<P>
As part of the city's efforts to clean up the environment, 50
such buses start running on the 20-km route today. A natural
gas filling station also opened for service today.
</P>
<P>
Drivers said that the natural gas cost is just about half of
that of petrol, and the amount of exhaust gases accounts for just
ten percent of the previous amount.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Xi'an is renovating other public vehicles for the
use of natural gas. The target for the year 2000 is to adjust
1,000 vehicles to use natural gas, and that for 2010 is to have all
the city's more than 30,000 buses, taxis and government vehicles
renovated into natural gas vehicles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
