<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA Makes Pratical Steps Against Superleague </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- UEFA, the European soccer
ruling body, made its first practical steps on Monday in a
campaign to prevent a breakaway superleague as a newly-formed
task force completed its first meeting.
</P>
<P>
The task force, named "European Club Football 2000", discussed
proposals to remodel the existing European Champions' League into
four groups of six, with a possible expansion from 24 to 32 clubs
and the merging of the exisiting Cup Winners' Cup and UEFA Cup
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Representatives to the meeting include those from six top
European clubs of Liverpool, Juventus, Ajax, Porto, Lyon and
Bayern Munich.
</P>
<P>
UEFA general secretary Gerhard Aigner denied that the task
force was a knee-jerk reaction to the threat of a breakaway
competition organised by the Milan-based marketing company Media
Partners which has proposed a pan-European league involving 36
clubs turning over billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting, generally described as useful by the
delegates of national leagues and the major clubs invited as part
of the task force, was harmonious and successful with an aim at
bringing UEFA's current competitions more up to date.
</P>
<P>
But Former German international Karl-Heinz Rummenigge, who
represented Bayern Munich, said money -- crucial to the clubs
threatening to break away -- had not been discussed.
</P>
<P>
The task force was essentially a working party put together
under the guidance of UEFA's Euro 2000 director Guido Tognoni and
chaired by UEFA vice-president Senes Erzik of Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
