<HEADLINE> S.Korea Seeking Closer Economic Ties With Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung Tuesday called for an expansion of economic cooperation
between South Korea and Germany, during German President Roman
Herzog's visit to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Kim asked Herzog to help encourage more German firms to invest
in South Korea during their meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also discussed a variety of issues of mutual
concern, including the Asian economic crisis and the political
situation on Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"President Kim expressed his hope that the German leader's
visit to Korea will provide a momentum toward expanding economic
cooperation between the two countries," said South Korea's
presidential spokesman Park Jie-won.
</P>
<P>
Herzog, the first foreign leader to visit South Korea since Kim
took office last February, arrived in Seoul on Tuesday for a
five-day visit. He was accompanied by 30 German industrialists and
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Germany is South Korea's second largest creditor. It has
pledged to loan 1.25 billion U.S. dollars to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Germany, also the fourth largest foreign investor in South
Korea, has invested 1.1 billion dollars in the country.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the German Credit Institution for
Reconstruction is expected to sign a 300-million-Deutschemark
(170-million-dollar) loan with Korea Development Bank on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
