<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Host Meeting on Cooperation in Mekong Subregion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Ministers and senior officials
from six countries would gather here from September 30 to October
2 to discuss new approaches for joint projects in the greater
Mekong subregion, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the 8th Conference on Economic Cooperation in the Greater
Mekong Subregion, the delegates would discuss a new concept, the
development of "economic zones" in the area, the Manila-based bank
said.
</P>
<P>
For example, industrial estates could be built near the border
of neighboring countries, such as Thailand and Laos. Both
countries can exploit comparative advantages in capital, natural
resources and labor for mutual benefit, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
"This will assist in the diversification, development and
restructuring of both economies and the ultimate objective of the
greater Mekong subregion cooperation," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the participants would also reaffirm their
long-term commitment to economic cooperation in the face of the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to the ADB, although the crisis is slowing down
projects in the energy sector largely because of lower power
demand in Thailand, there is continuing progress in other sectors
such as transport, telecommunications, human resource development,
tourism and environment.
</P>
<P>
The bank said 10 infrastructure projects have been either
completed or are under implementation in the subregion. About 1
billion U.S. dollars of resources have been mobilized to finance
these projects.
</P>
<P>
A draft Work Program 1998-2000 will also be presented during
the meeting. The delegates will focus not only on projects but
also on reducing non-physical barrier to cross-border activities
such as the streamlining of customs procedures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
