<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fair Trade Probe into Man United Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Office of Fair Trading
(OFT) has launched an inquiry into BSkyB's proposed 623 million
pounds (about 1.03 billion U.S. dollars) takeover of Manchester
United FC.
</P>
<P>
The Director General of Fair Trading, John Bridgeman, has
invited comments ahead of his decision on whether or not to refer
the deal to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for contributions is September 28. Mr. Bridgeman
will also consult the boards of Manchester United and BSkyB.
</P>
<P>
He will make his recommendations to Trade Secretary Peter
Mandelson on October 12. Mr. Mandleson has the final say on
whether or not to let the deal go ahead.
</P>
<P>
The OFT will try to establish if the deal constitutes a threat
to competition, in addition to any other issues that it deems to
be in the public interest.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United have already accepted the offer. The OFT is
automatically entitled to look into any deal worth more than 70m.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United Chief Executive Martin Edwards said he saw "
no obstacles" to the completion of the deal, but the performance
of the club's share price suggested that the city did not share
his optimism.
</P>
<P>
Shares opened on the London stock market on Monday at 221p and
rose steadily, but still failed to meet the BSKyB bid price of
240p, indicating that traders had doubts the deal would be
approved.
</P>
<P>
News of the inquiry came as rock drummer Roger Taylor, a
member of the band Queen, donated 10,000 pounds to the
Independent Manchester United Supporters' Association to help
fight the takeover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
