<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Rejects Sharing Formula of Marcos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential
Palace stood firm in rejecting the 75-25 sharing formula of former
president Ferdinand Marcos' wealth, Presidential Spokesman Jerry
Barican said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the sharing formula was made in a compromise deal
entered into by the Presidential Commission on Good Government
(PCGG) and the Marcoses during the previous Fidel Ramos
administration.
</P>
<P>
He said the sharing plan, although in favor of the government,
was not even approved by the then president Ramos.
</P>
<P>
"The supposed 75-25 compromise agreement between the Marcoses
and the Ramos administration was entered into by the PCGG without
the consent and approval of then president Fidel Ramos," he said.
</P>
<P>
Barican made the remarks in response to a proposal of Marcos
lawyer Reynaldo Dario for the government to withdraw its objection
to approving the compromise agreement.
</P>
<P>
Dario claimed that the withdrawal of the objection would
facilitate the release of 570-million-U.S.-dollar Marcos deposits
now held in an escrow account at the Philippine National Bank.
</P>
<P>
Marcos fled to Hawaii, the United States, in a popular revolt
in 1986 and died there three years later.
</P>
<P>
His successor, Corazon Aquino, established the PCGG to seek
Marcos wealth hidden around the world. However, it was until June
this year that the PCGG retrieved from two Swiss banks the 570
million dollars, part of the wealth Marcos collected during his 20
years' rule of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
