<HEADLINE> Shearer "not for Sale" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Newcastle United have
dismissed growing speculations that its star striker Alan Shearer
is set to leave the club.
</P>
<P>
The club's Chief Executive, Freddie Fletcher, spoke out on
Tuesday after a series of stories linked the England captain with
transfers to Premiership leaders Aston Villa, Chelsea and the
Italian giants Inter Milan.
</P>
<P>
"I can't believe the number of stories suggesting Alan Shearer
is leaving Newcastle," he said.
</P>
<P>
"He is not in talks with any other club. He is not for sale.
He is not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
"I have said it before and I repeat it again, Alan is an
integral part of Newcastle's future and that's the way its going
to stay -- and that's final."
</P>
<P>
Aston Villa in particular had been reported by several
newspapers to be stepping up their bid to try to sign Shearer.
</P>
<P>
Villa's Manager John Gregory was said to have set up talks
with the player's advisor Tony Stephens after the UEFA Cup first
round clash with Stromsgodset at Villa Park on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, some sources close to Newscastle United say that
Shearer has not dismissed the possibility of a move to Villa Park.
</P>
<P>
After raking in around 18 million pounds from the sale of
Dwight Yorke, Savo Milosevic and David Unsworth, Gregory has
ample funds at his disposal despite the 6.75 million signing of
Paul Merson.
</P>
<P>
When Gregory was asked about Shearer last week, he said: "I
would love him in my team -- he is the England number nine.
Suggestions of him being in decline after his injury are
rubbish."  
