<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Deficit Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The trade deficit in goods in
the Philippines dropped by 78.6 percent to 1.438 billion U.S.
dollars in the first seven months this year from the year-ago
level of 6.729 billion dollars, the National Statistics Office
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total trade in goods for the January-July period decreased
by 0.04 percent to 34.251 billion dollars from the year-ago level
of 34.264 billion dollars, the office said.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the country's revenue from exports increased
by 19.2 percent to 16.407 billion dollars while the expenditure
for imports fell by 12.9 percent to 17.844 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In July alone, the balance of trade reached 36 million dollars
and was in surplus for the second consecutive month. The total
trade for the month was 4.967 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
This year's monthly imports have so far been declining
year-on-year since the zero growth in January, the National
Statistics Office said.
</P>
<P>
Electronics and components, industrial machinery and equipment,
telecommunication equipment and electrical machinery, and other
items are the major imports for the country.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan, South Korea and Singapore are the
major trade partners of the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
