<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fighting Year 2000 Bug (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- All of China's stock
exchanges and securities companies will enter the 21st century by
the end of this month by turning the clocks in their computers
forward to December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
They have been required to test whether their computer systems
will be affected by the so-called year 2000 bug and whether the
stock market will run as normal when the new millenium comes.
</P>
<P>
"China's securities sector is keeping up with the advanced countries
in fixing ther year 2000 bug," said an official from China Securities
Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
With less than 500 days remaining until the calendar flips to
the year 2000, China, the most rapidly developing computer market
in the world, is tackling the year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
According to a timetable released by the State Council earlier
this month, China will fix all of its computer systems by the end
of March 1999, and will complete the checking and testing of the
fixed computer systems by the end of September 1999.
</P>
<P>
"It's not difficult technically, but it's really painstaking
and time-consuming to complete the huge task. China has more than 10
million computers and large numbers of embedded chips," said
Zhang Qi, a top official in charge of the year 2000 problem in
China.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 bug, also known as Y2K, arose from the fact that
most old mainframe computers still running keep track only of the
last two digits of each year. The computer assumes the first two
digits are 1 and 9. To the computer, 1999 is just 99. That means
that the computer will interpret 00 not as 2000 but as 1900,
throwing the date calculation off by 100 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fighting Year 2000 Bug (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Specialists estimate that the year 2000 bug biting the
computers can cause losses of 300 billion to 600 billion US
dollars globally.
</P>
<P>
China started to tackle the problem back in 1996. "Although
China still lags behind the advanced countries in fixing the
problem, it has drawn close attention in China's key departments,"
said Zhang Qi, director of the Product Department of the Ministry
of the Information Industry.
</P>
<P>
At early July, the Civil Aviation Administration of China
(CAAC) declared that it would solve the problem in the computer
systems for ticket-booking. So travelers need not worry about
booking tickets for the next century.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University's Founder Group Corp., one of China's
largest computer manufacturers, has promised that all of the
personal computers it has produced will be all right after
entering the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The State Seismology Bureau plans to replace the computers in
the seismological monitoring systems next month to avoid false
reporting of earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China's securities and futures sector will conduct
four overall tests in its computer systems by the end of June
1999. And those departments which fail to pass the tests will be
deprived of their licenses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese media have been reporting more on the year
2000 bug since the beginning of this year, and some newspapers run
special columns to discuss the problem and explain to the
readership whether malfunctions will be caused in hospitals and
whether they will receive repeated telephone bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
