<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fighting Year 2000 Bug (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A class aimed at training 5,000 specialists to cope with the
problem in China's ministries and departments was opened by the
Ministry of Information Industry last week.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance, the Ministry of Science and Technology
and China's commercial banks have offered financial support to
tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
In addition, new computers which have not been fixed are banned
from public sale, according to Zhang Qi.
</P>
<P>
However, the problem has not drawn enough attention in some
regions or by a hots of medium- and small-sized enterprises,
warned Dr. Sun Yuning, a specialist at the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, adding that some firms shut out external experts to
tackle their problems to keep business secrets.
</P>
<P>
"What I'm worrying about is that others' faults will damage our
work. China has entered the network era, and every error in the
network will affect the overall situation," said Liu Shuzhong, who
has tackled the year 2000 bug for more than two years for the Bank
of China, which plans to fix all its computer softwares by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
"People should be concerned closely with the problems caused by
high-tech development. But China's pace toward an information
society will not be reslowed by the difficulties," said Zhang Qi.
</P>
<P>
At present, China produces more than three million computers
every year, and the annual output is estimated to reach 10 million
in the year 2000, one tenth of world's total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
