<HEADLINE> Viagra Gets Marketing Approval from EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
authorized on Tuesday the anti-impotence drug Viagra for sale in
the 15 European Union (EU) member states.
</P>
<P>
The authorization was signed by European Industry Commissioner
Martin Bangemann in Strasbourg to clear the way for Pfizer Limited
Britain to market the drug.
</P>
<P>
The EU received applications to market Viagra from Pfizer
Limited Britain and Roerig Farmaceutici SpA, both units of the
American company.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner got the go-ahead for authorization from the
executive arm of the EU after the drug, produced by the American
company Pfizer, had first been endorsed in June by the European
Agency for the Evaluation of Medicinal Products and in August by
an EU medicines advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
Viagra is designed to treat erectile problems and not intended
for women and must not be administered to patients under the age
of 18, according to the opinion of the European Agency for the
Evaluation of Medicinal Products.
</P>
<P>
The leaflet on the medicine, which may only be supplied on
medical prescription, gives information on correct use,
contra-indications and undesirable side-effects.
</P>
<P>
Commission spokesman Jochen Kubosch said Tuesday that Viagra
may encounter sales obstacles in the national health services of
the member states, but the commission was not in a position to
comment on these.
</P>
<P>
The drug, which has been on the market since April this year in
the United States, may take from two weeks to several months to
reach consumers in the EU due to concerns over its side-effects
which include possible eye problems and an
uncomfortable heartbeat rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
