<HEADLINE> China Launches Large-Scale Hydropower Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China is launching a vigorous
drive to develop hydropower projects by utilizing foreign funds
totaling 4 billion US dollars, and has so far built 23 hydropower
stations with a total generating capacity topping 18.84 million kw.
</P>
<P>
"China has the richest hydroelectric power resources in the
world, with exploitable water energy resources estimated at 376
million kw, ranking first in the world," said a senior official
with the State Power Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The hydropower stations at the Three Gorges, Xiaolangdi and
Ertan in Sichuan province are among the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, China has so far completed 13
hydropower projects, with a combined generating capacity of 5.62
million kw at a cost of 1.442 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Five others, with a total capacity of 8.1 million kw, are being
built with 1.396 billion US dollars worth of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
China has been developing its hydroelectric power industry for
four decades, but especially since the reform and opening-up
drive began in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Total generating capacity and annual electricity output have
risen from 163,000 kw and 710 million kwh, respectively, in 1949,
to today's 52.17 million kw and 186.8 billion kwh. This makes
China third in generating capacity and production in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said there is still a lot that needs to
be done to make proper use of China's enormous resources, as its
total generating capacity accounts for only 13.8 percent of the
potential.
</P>
<P>
According to its medium-and long-range development plans, China
will have a capacity of 70 million kw by 2000, and by 2010 that
will rise to 125 million kw, or 33.1 percent of the country's
exploitable hydroelectric power resources.
</P>
<P>
The official further noted that 3.5 million kw will be added
annually, on average, in the remaining years of this century, and
from 2000 to 2010, hydroelectric power capacity will increase by
five million kw annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
