<HEADLINE> Foundation Establishes Fund to Aid Disaster Relief Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China Charity Foundation
(CCF), the largest charity organization in the country, is
preparing to establish a fund to aid fighters against natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
Yang Tuan, deputy director of the preparatory committee of the
fund, said funds will be used to provide aid to family members of
martyrs and individuals injured during disaster relief efforts,
including both soldiers and civilians.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that interest earned on the fund will be used to
improve living and healthcare conditions and help the
aforementioned recipients overcome difficulties.
</P>
<P>
A Shanghai enterprise has donated three million yuan (about
370,000 U.S. dollars) to the fund and the CCF expects total
donations to reach 30 million yuan (about 3.7 million
U.S. dollars) by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
The CCF, Beijing Municipal Telegraph Bureau and Wisdom Science
and Technology Enterprise have jointly launched an auction website
on the Internet to raise money for the fund.
</P>
<P>
China has suffered a series of natural disasters during 1998,
with an earthquake measuring 6.2 on the Richter Scale hitting the
Zhangbei area of north China's Hebei Province earlier in the year
killing 47 people, causing property damage of over 2.39 billion
yuan (about 300 million U.S. dollars) and leaving over 540,000
people homeless.
</P>
<P>
Heavy summer flooding in central, southeastern and northeastern
China killed 3,004 people, caused property damage of over 166.6
billion yuan (about 20.8 billion U.S. dollars) and affected over
223 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
