<HEADLINE> Air Fares in Asia-Pacific Rising in Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Air fares in the Asia
Pacific region continued to climb though the Asia financial crisis
has dragged many economies into a downturn, a global travel
services company said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
American Express released its latest issue of Asia-Pacific
Airfare Index Tuesday, saying that in the third quarter of 1998
air fares rose across all classes of travel. Premium and business
classes led the hike, with prices up by 4.8 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The fare increases, a continuing momentum since the second
quarter, indicate that airlines are readjusting their pricing
structure in the wake of the Asia financial turmoil, explained
Eric Meierhans, director of Purchasing Management Group of
American Express.
</P>
<P>
He said that "...airlines are trying to raise more revenue from
premium class travelers, who tend to be less sensitive to price
increases than leisure travelers."
</P>
<P>
The regional currency crisis has dealt a hard blow to leisure
travel and put heavy burdens on airlines, which now have to pay
higher U.S. dollar-denominated costs for fuel and debt.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices, one of the key costs for all airlines, are now at a
record low, but Asian airlines could not benefit from the drop in
greenback-denominated oil prices because of the devaluation of
currencies in their own countries.
</P>
<P>
The American Express index showed that air fares in Hong Kong
are now five percent higher than a year before. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
