<HEADLINE> US Ambassador Accused of Meddling with Mozambican </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The general secretary of the
Mozambican ruling party has accused the U.S. ambassador to Maputo
of interfering with the internal affairs of the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
Manues Tome, General Secretary of the Mozambique Liberation
Front Party (Frelimo), said here Monday that U.S. Ambassador to
Maputo Brian Curran should know that it's up to the Mozambicans
to decide on the elections to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Ambassador should give up passing the message through the
press, whatever the nature of the message is," Tome told Noticias
exclusively. "If he really wants to offer his advice or
criticism, he can do that through diplomatic channels."
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper Tuesday quoted the general secretary of
the Mozambican ruling party as saying that he was disappointed at
the remarks of the U.S. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports in Domingo weekly published in
capital Maputo Sunday, Curran said that the presidential and
legislative elections scheduled next year should be just,
democratic, transparent and serious with the participation of all
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador stated that if the Mozambican opposition
parties decide to boycott the elections, the U.S. government
would withdraw its financial support for the 1999 elections in
the African country.
</P>
<P>
"Political and financial blackmails are outdated, particularly
in an era of economic globalization when all nations should
respect each other," said Tome.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that no Mozambican ambassadors to the U.S. had
ever tried to arrogantly teach the Americans a lesson on
political or moral issues through the press.
</P>
<P>
The chief of the ruling party pointed out that the main
financial support for the Mozambican elections has come from the
European Union instead of the U.S..
</P>
<P>
An unidentified analyst in Maputo said that the U.S.
ambassador was interfering with the internal political affairs of
Mozambique by making those remarks and the U.S. always considers
itself the champion and model of democracy.
</P>
<P>
He added that no political parties could be forced to
participate in the elections, either local or general, in any
part of the world.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, transparency is not measured by how many
political parties participate in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Thus, it's meaningless for the U.S. ambassador to attempt to
teach the Mozambicans a lesson, the analyst said, adding that the
U.S. financial support will be welcomed but it should not contain
blackmail.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique held local elections in 33 towns and cities around
the country on June 30 this year, with the ruling Frelimo winning
a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition Mozambican National Resistance (Renamo)
together with other 15 small opposition parties boycotted the
elections.
</P>
<P>
During the 16-year war between the Frelimo and the Renamo, the
U.S. had all along been supporting the Renamo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
