<HEADLINE> $20M UNICEF-Supported Projects Underway in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Diverse development
projects are being undertaken throughout Ethiopia at a cost of 20
million U.S. Dollars under the auspices of the Ethiopian
government and the fourth country program of the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Herald newspaper Tuesday quoted program
coordinator Kebede Haile as saying that the projects have been
launched in 55 relatively more backward districts of different
regions at a cost of nine million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kebede said that during the past year alone various projects
involving construction as well as the equipping of internal
facilities of 153 health posts, 88 grain mills and 111 elementary
schools had been carried out.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator further said that 155 springs, 98
hand-operated water pumps, 17 ponds, 21,000 toilets and 57
nurseries have been developed or built last year.
</P>
<P>
In the nationwide program, construction of health, education,
water supply and environmental sanitation projects are being
carried out at a cost of 11 million Dollars, said Kebede.
</P>
<P>
These projects are expected to benefit 2.9 million people, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNICEF official, credit services to the tune
of 1.7 million U.S. Dollars have been given for 7,500 women and
similar assistances were also given for 17,000 farmers
encouraging them to undertake vegetable gardening activities.
</P>
<P>
About 1,500 stoves have also been distributed to farmers as
part of the effort to overcome shortage of firewood in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
