<HEADLINE> Guangzhou to Invest Heavily in Urban Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou Mayor Lin Shusen
recently announced that the city will spend some 60 billion yuan
for key projects over the next three years, with substantial
funding earmarked for the transportation and environmental
protection sectors.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, is one
of the most prosperous cities in China. The municipal government
is set to introduce a diversified system to attract capital for
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
"Top priority will be placed on the city's infrastructure and
environmental protection sectors." said Lin, adding that the
government plans to invest 40.1 billion yuan in 109 infrastructure
projects, including highways, and 20 billion yuan on a new airport.
</P>
<P>
Extensive efforts will also be made to control pollution and
expand the downtown greenbelt.
</P>
<P>
The local government will focus on the construction of four
highways, including the access road to the new airport. Total
investments in related projects are expected to hit 24.88 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government and railway department also plan to
build a railway linking Guangzhou and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The 18.48-km No. 1 Guangzhou Subway Line will be completed at a
cost 14 billion yuan and will enter operations by the end of this
year. Construction of the 21.34-km No. 2 Subway Line commenced in
July this year.
</P>
<P>
"Completion of the projects will greatly relieve existing
traffic problems," said Lin.
</P>
<P>
Lin pointed out that the city has allocated substantial funding
for construction in recent years. However, he noted the need for
more high quality image-building projects. Exemplary projects,
including roads, landscaped public squares and social venues are
currently under construction, and plans are being made for more
cultural centers and parks.
</P>
<P>
A group of exemplary projects, including the new Guangzhou
Stadium, Guangdong Olympic Sports Center and Guangzhou Theater,
will be contracted through international bidding.
</P>
<P>
The city of Guangzhou also plans to build new power plants and
both sewage and waste treatment facilities in the near
future. Fifty-five key programs will also be carried out to handle
industrial waste.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
