<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-British Joint Liaison Group Meets in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group (JLG) began its 43rd meeting here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The JLG, which meets alternately between Beijing, London and
Hong Kong, is meeting for the first time in Hong Kong after its
return to China on July 1 last year.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the two-day meeting, Senior Chinese
Representative Wang Guisheng extended a warm welcome to the
British delegation led by Senior Representative Ambassador Alan
Paul.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the JLG's mission has been basically finished
after Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the two sides still have some work to do --
to deal with the remaining issues, new issues arising from the
implementation of the past agreements reached by the two sides and
other issues which both sides deem necessary to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side is adopting a positive, friendly and practical
attitude towards the meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang said great changes had taken place since they last met
here some 15 months ago. One of the big changes was that the seats
between the guest and the host have been swapped.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that although the issue of Asian financial turmoil is
not on the formal agenda of the current meeting, it would be
touched upon during the discussions.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) has displayed exceptional courage and
wisdom in dealing with the effects of the Asian financial crisis
and achieved remarkable success.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Central Government resolutely
implements the principle of "one country, two systems," and will
never interfere in decisions made by the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
But "we support the measures the SAR government has taken to
maintain the linked exchange rate system and stabilize the order
of its financial market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the major factors contributing to the HKSAR's success in
dealing with the impact of the Asian financial crisis -- the sound
financial system, sound economic fundamentals and the hefty
foreign exchange reserves -- one is that Hong Kong had become a
SAR of the People's Republic of China before the financial turmoil
hit the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Central Government has made the firm
decision not to devaluate the Renminbi, which constitutes a
positive contribution not only to Hong Kong but also to Asia and
the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Paul said that after the handover, Hong Kong has
all important aspects being allowed to exercise a high degree of
autonomy promised in the Sino-British Joint Declaration on the
Question of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The British government firmly supports the resolute
determination of the Hong Kong SAR to defend the Hong Kong dollar
peg, he said.
</P>
<P>
The British side highly values this policy which is a vital
contribution to the region and the global financial stability as
well as to Hong Kong, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
