<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Seek Support For Anti-drug Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 15 (Xinhua)-- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) will convene a conference attended by
international sports federations this month to seek their support
for a proposed Olympic agency to lead the worldwide anti-drug
campaign.
</P>
<P>
IOC director general Francois Carrard said Tuesday that IOC
will also meet with Olympic summer sports federations on October
27 in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The governing body had announced last month at an emergency
meeting in Lausanne, that it planned to set up a special agency
to coordinate drug-testing programs around the world.
</P>
<P>
The summit was called following the Tour de France hit by drug
scandals this summer, where riders and team officials were
implicated in cases of systematic doping.
</P>
<P>
Carrard said the IOC hopes to get final approval for the
project during the February 2-4 world anti-doping conference in
Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Carrard said the four IOC vice presidents were close to
finalizing the makeup of their working groups on the main themes
of the conference: protection of athletes, political and legal
issues, ethics and prevention, and financial questions.
</P>
<P>
Vice president Dick Pound of Canada, in charge of the
financial issues, said the IOC planned to finance the drug agency
mainly through Olympic television rights fees and sponsorship
revenues.
</P>
<P>
Carrard said the IOC would open consultations in November with
governments on getting their assistance in fighting drug use in
sports. The governments of Australia and the United States, hosts
of the next two Olympics, would be among those consulted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
