<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Urges Arafat to Compromise in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu here Tuesday urged Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat to make compromise in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made this call in a press conference held after
holing talks with visiting Uzbekistan President Islam Karimov.
During the talks, the two leaders discussed the issues of
bilateral economic cooperation and the situation in Central Asia
and the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
"I am not going to talk about in detail about the ongoing peace
talks between Israelis and Palestinians, but I can assure you that
if Arafat can make political decisions on key issues, there will
be an agreement," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks resumed last Wednesday
after U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross' return to the
region. They touched upon interim issues such as Israel's troop
redeployment in the West Bank, Gaza airport and seaport, the safe
passage linking the West Bank and Gaza and security cooperation
between Israel and Palestine. But no substantial progress was
reported so far.
</P>
<P>
On the redeployment issue, Israel blamed the Palestinian side
for its refusal of Israel's 13 percent withdrawal plan, in which 3
percent would be turned into a nature reserve with Israel's
control of security. The Palestinian side said this 3 percent must
be turned in to Area B, in which the Palestinan side should be
responsible for its civil administration.
</P>
<P>
"If you (Palestinian side) want an agreement, then you will get
one soon," Netanyahu said, adding that Arafat must take tough
measures to fight terrorism and make political decisions on the
key issues discussed with Israel.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Netanyahu said he had discussed with Karimov
future economic cooperation between the two countries and the
issue of cooperation in fighting Islamic fundamentalism which
poses direct threat to Israel.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he named Iran and some other countries and
urged Russia to stop supplying missile development technology to
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral economic cooperation is on the main agenda for
Karimov's three-day official visit to Israel which began on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Karimov worked out nine agreements during the
talks and signed them just before holding the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The agreement signed included bilateral trade and economic
cooperation and cooperations in the fields of technology,
culture, agriculture, health and environment.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Karimov held talks with his Israeli counterpart
Ezer Weizman, in which Weizman expressed his worries about the
stalled peace process and asked Karimov to help break the
impasse.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday afternoon, Karimov went to Ramallah to discuss the
peace process and bilateral issues with Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
