<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers' Way of Life Changing Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Economic development has
changed the outlook in Chinese rural areas and has also changed
Chinese farmers' customs and way of life.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers used to ignore modern etiquette, but now more
and more villagers consider etiquette important in their contacts
with outside world.
</P>
<P>
Knowing little about etiquette, Zhangshi village in North
China's Hebei Province once failed to cooperate with a printing
plant in the city of Baoding in Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The head of the Zhangshi village paper mill went to sign a
contract with the printing plant, but his rude style of
conversation and informal dress spoiled the negotiation atmosphere
and resulted in an unpleasant suspension of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the importance of etiquette, the village leaders
called on their people to take etiquette lessons. Now these
villagers are adapting themselves to modern habits in their daily
lives.
</P>
<P>
Chinese rural areas used to be very quiet in the evening
because farmers went to sleep early after a day's hard work, but
now the countryside is lively at night.
</P>
<P>
Karaoke and yangko (a rural folk dance) are becoming popular,
and in the evening many farmers go outdoors for fun and they have
a jolly time singing and dancing.
</P>
<P>
"People are more affluent than before, so they want to enjoy
themselves in their free time," said Li Yuzhan, the head of
Muzhuang village in Hebei.
</P>
<P>
Many farmers are also changing their taste in food, as their
diet now includes more fish and meat as well as the traditional
coarse cereals.
</P>
<P>
Liu Li, deputy secretary-general of the China Food Association,
said that changes in the farmers' diet show that more of them have
come to know about a balanced diet and they are now eating in a
more healthy way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merger of Universities Lends New Competitive Edge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zhejiang University, the
largest comprehensive institute of higher learning in China, was
brought into being here today, with the ambitious goal of ranking
itself among the world's first-class universities in next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The new university is a combination of four universities
--Zhejiang University, Hangzhou University, Zhejiang Agricultural
University and Zhejiang Medical University-- in east China's
Zhejiang Province. It is now the largest university in China, with
11 branches of learning, over 10,000 faculty members and some
30,000 students.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing attended the inauguration ceremony, and
said the initiation of the new university represents another step
China has taken to reform its system of higher learning and will
certainly promote the rational utilization of educational
resources in the country.
</P>
<P>
Modeled after those of the former Soviet Union, Chinese
colleges and universities established during the 1950s and 1960s
were run by the state, State Council departments, industries, or
provinces or regions. This led to a surfeit of specialized
colleges, a waste of resources and low efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The new university's president, Pan Yunhe, said the university
will put emphasis on research and encourage creativity, and make
breakthroughs in major fields. He pledged to bring the total
number of graduate students in the university to over 10,000 by
the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The new university will focus on establishing new disciplines,
especially in the frontier sciences, so as to enhance its
competitiveness, Pan said.
</P>
<P>
The new university is expected to get a total of 800 million
yuan (about one million US dollars) in funding from the central
treasury and provincial government, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
