<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Plane Ticketing Makes Debut in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China today became one of the
first countries in the world to sell electronic airplane tickets
to passengers.
</P>
<P>
China is the first place that the United States-based United
Airlines (UA) chose to start its worldwide campaign to spread the
use of the paperless E-ticket.
</P>
<P>
China's move will be followed by Singapore, Germany, Italy,
France, Belgium and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The electronic ticket, which will be available at UA's Beijing
office from today, is carried through the airline's computer
system instead by the traveler himself. In fact, he does not need
any ticket when boarding a UA flight. He has just to show that the
credit card that he used to buy the E-ticket matches the records
in the computer.
</P>
<P>
"We picked China as one of the first places to implement
E-ticket service because it is easiest to do it here," said
Christopher Lin, general manager of UA in China.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese authorities have had a very supportive
attitude toward UA's E-ticket service in China.
</P>
<P>
UA has already set up 11 customer representative service
offices around China. It is expected to win approval to set up
another ten offices in the country this year.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that, as a technological innovator in the world
aviation industry, UA is working on a software system to enable
its computer ticketing network to interface with various ticketing
networks around the world, including the one in China.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that UA will make E-tickets available at all its agents
around China next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted, though the use of credit cards is still
not very common in China, past experience has proved that UA will
probably see a multifold increase of business in the new operation
in only a few years after introducing it to China.
</P>
<P>
UA now accounts for one-third of the air flight market from the
U.S. to China.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ronghua, deputy director of the international department
of the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC), said that
China needs the help of UA, the world's largest airline, with
invaluable expertise, experience and technology.
</P>
<P>
This year, China will invest three billion yuan (362 million US
dollars) to update its airlines computer ticketing system and
build a commercial information network for the aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
CAAC has already connected its administration computer system
with those of foreign airlines, such as Ansett of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Since it began trial service of E-tickets on domestic flights
in the U.S. in 1994, UA has achieved annual sales of 3.4 million
E-tickets worldwide in 1997. Last year, E-tickets made up over
half the total number of tickets that UA sold around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0134 </DOCNO>
