<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Irish Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern today praised China's efforts on human rights, saying
he has been encouraged over the past years by the important steps
China has taken in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, the first Irish prime minister to visit China since
the two countries forged diplomatic ties 19 years ago, delivered a
speech to an audience of more than 100 at the Foreign Affairs
College this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he is also encouraged by efforts
currently being made to ensure the success of the human rights
dialogue between China and the European Union. "We believe that
this dialogue has the potential to yield very positive results and
we are heartened already by evidence of transparency and sincerity
on all sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the visit to China by United Nations high
commissioner for human rights Mary Robinson, former Irish
president, has been very significant, and he voiced the hope that
it will assist and intensify constructive human-rights dialogue
between China and the international community.
</P>
<P>
"Human rights are universal values common to all humanity, when
we discuss them, they must be as matters of collective mutual
concern, not as issues which divide us," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ahern also expressed high appreciation for China's economic
development, saying China has telescoped into one generation what
it has taken other countries centuries to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
He said he is fully confident that China will succeed in its
extraordinary voyage of change and that in so doing it will have
enriched the world. "The past two decades have seen sustained
rapid modernization unlike that in any other period in China's
long history, and the next two decades promise more of the same."
he said.  
</P>
