<HEADLINE> Northwest Airlines to Resume China Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Northwest Airlines of the
United States will resume its flights to Beijing and Shanghai on
September 18 and 21, respectively, a senior company official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Northwest used to operate nine flights between Beijing and
Detroit and Shanghai-Tokyo-U.S. each week. The resumption has come
after more than 6,000 pilots ended a strike September 12, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that operation of one fourth of Northwest's 1,700
flights worldwide has returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
Northwest previously resumed its flights to China in 1984.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the sharing of flight codes between Northwest
and Air China, this country's national flag carrier, will take
effect on October 25. By then, the number of two-way flights
operated by the two companies will rise to 17 each week, with
overall carrying capacity doubling the present one, the official
said.  
