</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Rapid Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China has registered rapid
economic growth over the past 20 years, according to an official
of the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Shao Zongming, deputy director of the bureau, gave this remark
at a seminar on the publication of a book named "Splendid
Achievements Over 20 Years".
</P>
<P>
The book, compiled by the bureau, praises the splendid
achievements China has scored, analyzes in depth the problems
China's economy faces, and brings up suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Shao noted that China is now listed No. 7 in terms of economic
strength in the world, with the annual economic growth rate for
the past 20 years reaching 9.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1997 China's output of grain reached
494.17 million tons, while the output of many industrial products
was also listed high in the world.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the investment in fixed assets has totalled
14,000 billion yuan, including 2,530 billion yuan in 1997 alone.
A batch of key infrastructural projects were constructed during
the period, such as the Qinshan Nuclear Power Station and the
Beijing-Kowloon railway.
</P>
<P>
With this economic development, a "buyer's market" is taking
shape in China. In 1997, the retail sales in the country reached
2,729.9 billion yuan-worth, some 20 times those in 1978.
</P>
<P>
China is now opening still wider to the outside world, as it
has set up trade relations with more than 200 countries and
regions and it has used 348.3 billion US dollars of foreign funds
in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The living standards of the Chinese people are improving as their
incomes rise. In 1997, the per capita disposable income for
urban residents reached 5,160 yuan, registering an annual growth
rate of 6.2 percent, while the per capita net income for farmers
reached 2,090 yuan, with an annual growth rate of 8.1 percent.
 
</P>
