<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Lower in Quiet Dealings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
drifted down to a weaker close Tuesday amid quiet dealings.
</P>
<P>
With the Japanese markets closed for a public holiday, there
was little to influence the local unit.
</P>
<P>
"There's not a great deal of volume out there. It's been pretty
thin, a pretty dull day on the currency," Glen Howard, portfolio
manager at Perpetual Funds Management, said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended here at 59.49 U.S. cents from 59.72
at Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
On the day the Australian dollar traded between 59.25 and 59.63
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the currency market would continue to focus on U.S.
politics and its effect on stocks and the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"And on the other side of it, we'll still be looking at the yen
and see what's happening tomorrow -- if we hear any more about
possible banking reforms in Japan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Local traders also believed that the key event to watch out for
will be an address to be made by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan to the U.S. House Banking Committee early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Howard said, "I think he will be watched very closely to see
whether he does give any clues on whether or not they have moved
to an easing bias or whether they are in a neutral bias."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 79.24 Japanese yen from 78.89
and 1.009 German marks from 1.0178. 
</P>
</TEXT>
