<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Troops Disperse Protestors In Maseru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho army Tuesday
morning dispersed groups of youths from opposition parties, who
attacked civil servants, causing panic among commuters going to
work, said reports reaching here from Maseru, capital of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The protestors seized government vehicles in Maseru and forced
civil servants driving to work to abandon their cars.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been brought under control after the army
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Army trucks are patrolling the streets of Maseru and groups of
police officers were stationed at strategic points along the main
streets, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The violence took place after South African Defense Minister
Joe Modise held the second round of talks with the Lesotho
cabinet and army on problems in the Lesotho Defense Force (LDF).
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the protestors were against the
intervention of South Africa and other countries in the region in
attempt to resolve a political crisis in Lesotho arising from the
alleged rigging of results of Lesotho's general elections in May.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, protesters gathered outside the residence of
South African High Commissioner to Lesotho, Japhet Ndhlovu, in
Maseru to protest against the presence of Modise and his
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Raido Lesotho announced Tuesday that the talks between Modise
and the Lesotho government were fruitful, but it did not report
details.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, South African Press Association quoted reliable
sources as reporting that the defense ministers of South Africa,
Botswana and Zimbabwe are due to meet in Gabarone later Tuesday
in the latest efforts to resolve problems in the Lesotho army
which has contributed to political instability in the country.
</P>
<P>
On Friday night of last week, LDF commander Makhula Mosakheng
reportedly made announcement of resignation on national radio at
gun point.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe make up the Southern
African Development Community's so-called troika on Lesotho,
established in 1994 to mediate a solution to then political
crisis in that country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
