<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Foreign Exchange Infractions (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new set of regulations on foreign exchange management does
not mean that China has returned to a total and rigid foreign
exchange control, the spokesman stressed.
</P>
<P>
Great changes have taken place in China's foreign exchange
revenues and expenditures since reform of the foreign exchange
system in 1994, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
International revenues and expenditures have been balanced for
several years in a row, and foreign exchange reserves have been
increasing fast, he added.
</P>
<P>
In late 1996, China accepted Article VIII of the International
Monetary Fund Agreement and started to allow the Chinese currency
yuan become convertible under current accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
This effectively advanced the fresh growth of China's foreign
trade and the use of overseas funds, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"We will value this reform achievement by continuing the
practice of letting the yuan be convertible under current
accounts, improving the management of capital accounts, and
safeguarding a balance between international revenue and
expenditure for national economic security," he added.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations regarding control of foreign exchange
published recently are, under the prerequisite of persisting in
the RMB convertibility under current accounts, supplemental and
revised contents based on the existing rules on foreign exchange
control, he said.
</P>
<P>
This bears in mind violations discovered in the nationwide
inspections on foreign exchange to prevent loopholes in examining
validity of current accounts for the RMB convertibility and to
improve management of approving foreign exchange revenue and
expenditure of capital accounts, he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said he hopes the newly published regulations
will help increase more legal foreign exchange inflow, halt
illegal foreign exchange outflow, and plug loopholes in foreign
exchange dealings.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations have not only made stipulations on foreign
exchange tradings by banks, enterprises and individuals, but also
set higher standards for supervisory organizations.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman explained that improvement of the regulations is
focused on ensuring the legal flow of foreign exchange, which will
not affect the principle of RMB convertibility under current
accounts, or go back to the past practice of total and rigid
foreign exchange control.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises which need foreign exchange for current accounts
and individuals who want hard currencies for private matters can
go, as usual, to purchase foreign exchange with valid papers
stipulated by relevant regulations, the spokesman emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He added that halting the abnormal flow of foreign exchange
will better satisfy enterprise and individual normal demands for
foreign exchange in the long run.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Spokesman On U.N. Taiwan Refusal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Zhu Bangzao expressed China's sincere appreciation for
the vast majority of United Nations member states who have upheld
justice on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remark here this afternoon at his regular press
conference when asked to comment on the latest refusal by the
General Committee of the U.N. General Assembly to a proposal
concerning Taiwan's so-called "representation" at the U.N.
</P>
<P>
He also advised a small group of countries concerned not to
harm the sentiments of the Chinese people again.
</P>
<P>
Zhu reiterated that China's representation at the U.N. was
thoroughly settled when the U.N.'s 26th General Assembly passed
Resolution 2758 in 1971, and that Taiwan, a province of China,
lacks qualification for U.N. membership.
</P>
<P>
However, Taiwan has encouraged a small group of countries to
stage a proposal to list Taiwan's so-called "representation" on
the agenda of the U.N. General Assembly, which, of course, met
with opposition from the vast majority of U.N. member states, Zhu
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
