<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Continue Rally on Wall Street Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
continued its upward march Tuesday on the back of a 150-point gain
on Wall Street overnight and a particularly strong banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The positive sentiment did not extend to the gold sector
however, which tumbled 2.9 percent as the spot price of bullion
traded lower.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries index ended 44.1 points or 1.76
percent firmer at 2,554.3, meaning the market has gained 86 points
so far this week.
</P>
<P>
"New York added to the buying momentum here," Shaw
Stockbroking's Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
A stronger Hong Kong market also aided the positive sentiment,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the All Resources added 16.6 points to close at 996.3
and the industrials index climbed 78.2 points to 4,486.1.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 30.3 points lower at 1,015.7 and gold
bullion in Sydney was trading 70 U.S. cents softer at 289.3 U.S.
dollars per fine ounce.
</P>
<P>
In the broader resources sector, BHP climbed 20.7 cents, Rio
Tinto jumped 71.4 cents, Comalco firmed 15 cents and WMC added 6
cents.
</P>
<P>
Australia's big four banks all recorded solid gains, with NAB
adding 53.2 cents, ANZ 38 cents, Westpac 34.5 cents and CBA 46.4
cents.
</P>
<P>
Media giant News Corp. gained 34.2 cents and its preferred
scrip improved by 37 while Telstra firmed 2.2 cents topping the
volume table with 14.12 million installment receipts changing
hands.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 250.76 million valued at 729.79
million Australian dollars (437.87 million U.S. dollars). Rises
outpaced falls by 524 to 421 with 401 stocks remaining steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
