<HEADLINE> China to Launch Seed Quality Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Agriculture,
the State Administration for Industry and Commerce, and the State
Bureau for Quality and Technology Supervision will jointly launch
a large-scale inspection of seed quality and sales across China.
</P>
<P>
The inspection begins today and will end on September 30, said
Lu Ming, vice-minister of agriculture, at a press conference here
today. He added that the purpose of this move is to rectify the
seed market and ensure farm production.
</P>
<P>
They intend to check seed suppliers to discover whether they
are qualified and whether or not they are engaging in any illegal
activities in their operation.
</P>
<P>
"Those found violating the law will be punished severely," Lu
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that seeds play a key role in agricultural production
and increased income for farmers, especially at present when the
flooded areas are rebuilding and the autumn planting is about to
begin across the country.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Administration for Industry and
Commerce said the current seed market needs rectification as
sometimes fake seeds are reported to appear on the market.
</P>
<P>
China pays close attention to seed quality, and in the past has
launched about ten such seed-inspection campaigns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
