<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000 Congolese Refugees Flee into Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Gu Ming)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 5,000 refugees
from the war-torn Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have fled
into neighboring Tanzania, United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By Tuesday morning, the DRC refugees who crossed Lake
Tanganyika into Tanzania to escape the battles between the rebels
and the troops loyal to President Laurent Kabila's government had
reached 4,935, said Jean Durieux, head of the UNHCR sub-office in
Kigoma, where the refugees are accommodated.
</P>
<P>
A number of Congolese people began to flee from Kalemie on the
western shore of the lake. "There has been heavy fighting in and
out of the town," Durieux told Xinhua over telephone.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the refugees had mainly come from
the eastern Congolese towns of Uvira and Baraka.
</P>
<P>
The DRC is currently locked in a civil war in which the rebels
want to topple the government of President Kabila. The revolt
began on August 2 in the town of Goma in the third largest
African country.
</P>
<P>
Durieux said that most of the refugees have been in good
conditions, but there are also some who have been wounded.
</P>
<P>
The refugees are currently taking shelter at the Nyarugusu
camp, some 160 kilometers northeast of Kigoma town and have
sufficient food supplies thanks to the assistance of the World
Food Program (WFP), non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and the
UNHCR, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Although the Nyarugusu camp has a capacity of accommodating as
many as 50,000 refugees, there are plans to use Lufugu camp in
the southwest of the Kigoma town in case that the Congolese
refugees increased drastically, said UNHCR senior external
relations officer Vincent Parker in Dar es Salaam Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR has also requested the Tanzanian government to
provide a third camp site for the arriving Congolese refugees,
but so far the agency has not received any response, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local media said that 100 soldiers of the DRC
government troops, armed with guns and ammunitions, fled the
tight fighting in the eastern part of the country and arrived in
Kigoma Sunday.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR officials pointed out that accommodation of the
combatants is not within its scope of UNHCR services as the group
of people are non-civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
