<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Promises No More Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has assured the world and Nigerians that
there would be no more election annulments, as the country has
embarked on another transition to civil rule process.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions on a British Broadcasting Corporation
(BBC) program "Network Africa" Monday, Abubakar implored
Nigerians not to entertain fears of any annulment under the
current transition program.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there will be any cause for that. We don't
have any fears. We have got an Independent Electoral Commission
(INEC) with people of honor and repute," he said.
</P>
<P>
Repeating his earlier statement that the era of military coup
is gone with the end of the cold war, Abubakar said: "Now that
there are no more cold war, any right thinking military men will
think twice before contemplating to topple any government."
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, a career soldier who took office in June this year
after the sudden death of late leader General Sani Abacha,
accused the civilian society of covertly or overtly encouraging
military coup.
</P>
<P>
"The civilians encourage the soldiers and whenever there is
coup, the civilians start flying about, appealing and looking for
appointments in the same military government," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is my belief that both the soldiers, civilians and
everybody in Nigeria would have learnt a lesson. Whoever is in
power should ensure good government and give amenities,
facilities, protection, health care and education to all
Nigerians and I am sure nobody will even contemplate of toppling
a government," he added.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has promised to hand power over to an elected
civilian government in May next year. Twenty-five political
groups have applied for registration by the INEC to contest in
the new transition program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set Up First Minor Export Crop Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to set up the first minor export crop company at Matale in
Central Province to improve minor export crop cultivation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
About 15,000 acres (6,073 hectares) of land in the Matale area
have been brought under such cultivation so far under a program,
Export Department officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government will give instructions and assistance to improve
this cultivation while new land will be added for this purpose,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that there is considerable demand for Sri
Lankan minor crops in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Therefore the farmers can get a good income from this
cultivation, the officials said, adding that the government has
been encouraging the farmers to engage in the cultivation by
taking several steps including giving them financial aid and other
necessary assistance.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's minor export crops include cocoa, cinnamon,
cardamom, cloves, pepper and coffee, which account for a
considerable proportion of Sri Lanka's agricultural exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
