<HEADLINE> Forum Discusses Pawnshops In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A national forum on
pawnshops, the first since this business was resumed in China ten
years ago, wound up here September 13.
</P>
<P>
The forum, sponsored by a national pawn industry committee and
the Liaoning Provincial Academy of Social Sciences, drew over 120
scholars, financial officials and pawnbrokers from across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The participants had extensive discussions about the present
situation and prospects for the pawn business in China, and called
for increased efforts to build up a legal framework for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
China outlawed pawnshops in 1949. But in the last ten
years, about 1,300 pawnshops have sprung up across the country,
with total capital assets of about eight billion yuan (about
963 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
