<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on Human Rights High Commissioner's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- With efforts by both sides,
the visit to China paid by Mary Robinson, United Nations high
commissioner for human rights, has been successful.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao made this comment
 at today's regular press conference when asked to comment on the
visit by Robinson from September 9 to 15.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in China, Zhu said, she met with both Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Vice-Premier of the State Council Qian
Qichen.
</P>
<P>
She talked with Chinese officials in Beijing, Shanghai and
Tibet, and also held seminars with representatives of science,
religion, education and women, and several non-governmental
organizations. Robinson also had wide contacts with laid-off
workers, farmers and students, Zhu said, adding that both sides
signed a cooperative memorandum of intent.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that Robinson learned of the progress China has made
on human rights and she saw that the Chinese economy and social
and legal reform has made great progress, and that the historical
and cultural heritage of Tibet have been well protected.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that both sides have reached common ground and
Robinson has established good working relations with China.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged views on bilateral cooperation and
China positively echoed Robinson's reference to cooperation, Zhu
said, adding that both sides will conduct concrete consultations
for implementing the details of the cooperative memorandum of
intent at a proper time.  
</P>
