<HEADLINE> S. Korea Repatriates Five Foreigners Infected with HIV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has repatriated
five foreigners infected with the HIV virus in the first half of
this year, the Health and Welfare Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This move has brought the total number of repatriated foreign
HIV carriers to 89 since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The virus causes the deadly disease known as the AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Under a South Korean regulation, foreign workers are required
to submit documents proving that they are HIV-negative before
entering the country while South Korean employers are required to
have their foreign workers take regular medical check-ups.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry said, it is difficult to test foreigners
who entered South Korea illegally.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of June this year, a total of 811 South Koreans
were spotted infected with the virus and among them are 104
women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
