<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Teenagers Optimistic About Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Sixty percent of South
African teenagers think that they will have bright future in
their homeland, according to a report by the local Research
Surveys.
</P>
<P>
In its report released Monday, Research Surveys said following
a survey last month of 800 teenagers, it had been found that 60
percent felt optimistic about their future in the country, with
24 percent feeling neither optimistic nor pessimistic, and only
16 percent feeling pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that white teenagers were less optimistic than
their black counterparts, with only 38 percent falling into the
optimistic category.
</P>
<P>
In response to three descriptions of their possible attitudes
toward staying or leaving South Africa, 71 percent of teenagers
thought of many good reasons to stay in the country and no good
reasons to leave.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two percent of teenagers felt that there were many good
reasons to stay, but that there were also many good reasons to leave.
</P>
<P>
Only seven percent of the total sample felt that there were no
good reasons to stay and many good reasons to leave South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Research Surveys said the sample, comprising boys and girls
between the ages of 13 to 20, had been scientifically weighted and
was therefore representative of black and white teenagers in terms
of age and population distribution.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been challenged by increasing unemployment
and crimes. Tens of thousands South Africans, mainly the white,
are so pessimistic about the currently crucial social problems
that many of them have immigrated to western countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
