<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Archeologists Cooperating with Overseas Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists and
their overseas counterparts have cooperated recently in joint
projects which have uncovered several significant ruins and
cultural relics within the borders of China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Social Sciences' (CASS) Institute of
Archeology together with the cultural relics office of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) unearthed an ancient
cultural site on an island near downtown Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At this site they discovered at least 20 tombs dating back to
the Neolithic Age and the Bronze Age, together with a number of
building ruins and earthenware, jadeware and stone artifacts.
</P>
<P>
"All the cultural relics and ruins there from as far back as
3,500 to 5,000 years ago will provide solid material for studying
the remote history of Hong Kong and its cultural exchanges with
neighboring areas," said Miao Yajuan, a CASS research fellow.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen of the 20 tombs had human remains, the first such group
of remains ever found in Hong Kong, Miao said. This may allow
researchers to further their studies of physical characteristics,
average longevity and pathological features among the ancient
inhabitants of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Together with a team of archeologists from Harvard University,
the institute unearthed the ruins of an ancient temple near
Shangqiu in central Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
They found many cultural relics from all the early, middle and
late stages of the Longshan culture, including a 66-sq-m earth
foundation and a bank of house ruins.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chinese experts and archeologists from the
University of Minnesota surveyed ancient sites within the
Huaihe River Basin in Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the institute and a Japanese cultural research
organization recently began excavations at the site of ancient
capital Chang'an, about three km northwest of present-day Xi'an,
the capital of Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
After probing the layout of the Guigong Palace, they found a
huge foundation of four palaces, and they have now completed a
5,000-sq-m excavation at the No. 2 palace foundation, Miao added.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
