<HEADLINE> More Embassies in Uganda Close for Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Some more foreign missions
accredited to Uganda were closed after receiving threat calls
from anonymous callers, a senior police officer told Xinhua Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of Uganda Police Force, Bob Ngobi, said security
around the foreign missions in Uganda has been beefed up and the
police will respond immediately after receiving calls for help.
</P>
<P>
"There are some people who take advantage of the bombing incident
in Nairobi and Dar-es-Salaam to threaten people here and we have
carried out tough preventive measures for it," he said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
As for the reported closing of U.S. Embassy, the British High
Commission, the Royal Danish Embassy, the World Bank Uganda Office and
the European Union office, he said he could not confirm, adding that
security should be the key reason for the move of these agencies.
</P>
<P>
The officer, however, said the United Nations Development Program
in Uganda had received at least two threat calls last week and the
U.N. agency is taking utmost precaution against the bomb threats.
</P>
<P>
Since the bombing in U.S. embassies in Nairobi and Dar-es-Salaam
in early August, Kampala has been receiving more threat calls than
ever before. Kampala Police Chief Benjamin Namanya told Xinhua
more police force is deployed in and around what people
consider soft targets.
</P>
<P>
More police officers have been trained to guide people. Security
pamphlets have been distributed to educate civilians about bombs and
to give tips on what to do in an emergency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
