<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Foreign Exchange Infractions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
stepping up its crackdown on foreign exchange infractions such as
the evasion of foreign exchange payment and illegal dealings in
foreign exchange amid a resurgence in black market activities.
</P>
<P>
Responding to reporters at a press conference, a spokesman for
the State Administration of Foreign Exchange said that the growth
of such infractions is a result of the influence of the external
economic environment and has already exerted a negative impact on
China's foreign exchange balance, and thus should be firmly
combated.
</P>
<P>
Measures already taken include a general examination of the
foreign exchange settlement activities of enterprises, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In these examinations, the accounts of the enterprises are
carefully checked to see that every purchase or payment in foreign
exchange is truly connected to import dealings with adequate
imported commodities.
</P>
<P>
"Our determination is firm to fight against the illegal
activities such as breaches of exchange regulations or purchasing
foreign exchange with the help of forged documents," the spokesman
noted.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, we've asked the exchange department to enhance
internal management and strictly punish personnel who are involved
in illegal trading," he added.
</P>
<P>
In support of this fight, a series of new regulations on
exchange control were formulated and promulgated recently, and
they are expected to offset the shortcomings of existing foreign
exchange control.
</P>
<P>
According to new regulations, a financial institution found to
have broken with foreign exchange sale and payment regulations
will be suspended from foreign exchange settlement business, and
administrative or disciplinary penalties will be applied to those
persons involved in such activities.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade right of enterprises found to be involved in
illegal dealings of certain amounts of money will be revoked.
Criminal penalties will be given to law-breakers and any
accomplices working with the customs, banking and exchange
departments.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told reporters that a computerized network will
be launched in the near future linking customs, banks and foreign
exchange control departments, which will ensure the synchronical
transmitting and checking of the inflow and outflow of goods and
foreign exchange. This is expected to leave less room for illegal
activities.
</P>
<P>
"The above measures have already effectively reduced illegal
dealings," the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Nuo Culture Museum Lacks Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A Nuo culture museum in
Tongren Prefecture in southwest China's Guizhou Province is badly
in need of funds to protect its relics and photographs.
</P>
<P>
This is the only museum of its kind in the country. Nuo, a
ceremony to drive away ghosts or pestilence, originated in ancient
times with the practice of totem worship.
</P>
<P>
The museum borrowed three rooms of the Dongshan temple as
exhibit halls in March 1991, and out of 100-plus rare photos
collected by the museum, a dozen are hanging unprotected and the
rest are piled together behind the hall where they are
deteriorating from the elements, according to eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
Only two people are taking care of the museum, and a large
number of photos were stolen several years ago because there are
no guards.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou has the richest Nuo culture among southern Chinese
provinces, and Tongren Prefecture has 70 percent of the province's
Nuo cultural heritage. More than 5,000 artisans of different
ethnic minorities are now engaged in Nuo cultural activities in
the area, with more than 500 Nuo opera groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
