<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Foreign Exchange Infractions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman urged people to be aware of the dangers of
illegal trading in foreign exchange in the black market for the
sake of state economic security.
</P>
<P>
He called "misleading and dangerous" the thinking that foreign
exchange settlements are only dealings between the yuan and
foreign exchanges, which cannot trigger criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman called for drawing lessons from the recent
financial crisis in Southeast Asia and Russia which he believes
partly stemmed from uncontrolled foreign exchange dealings which
increased the chances for international speculators and caused the
devaluation of local currencies and the outflow of state wealth.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that smuggling, money laundering, and
profiteering are in many cases behind these illegal activities
which pose great dangers to society.
</P>
<P>
He also called the attention to those who spread rumors on the
black market, shaking investors' confidence and arousing social
turmoil.
