<HEADLINE> China's Fishing Ban Ends Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The last contingent of
Chinese fishermen idled by the summer fishing ban are allowed to
resume fishing in the Yellow and East China seas at midnight
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Today is the last day of the ban which took effect in June. An
official from the Ministry of Agriculture today called this year's
ban "successful".
</P>
<P>
"China has expanded the fishing moratorium in terms of both
length and scope, with a continual decline in the number of
fishing vessels found in violation of the ban," according to
the official from the ministry's Fisheries Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The moratorium idled 90,000 Chinese fishing boats, including
some 22,000 vessels operating in the East China Sea. A recent
check revealed that only two per thousand boats in the East China
Sea violated the fishing this year's ban, compared with 3.5 per
thousand during last summer's moratorium.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the improvement to an increasing
awareness of the need for the ban and the efforts of local
governments to strengthen both management and supervision.
</P>
<P>
He substantiated the fact that falling output in the first half
of the year and the extension of moratorium period have prompted
some fishermen to ignore the ban.
</P>
<P>
Fishing with trawl nets and other "hazardous fishing equipment"
has been banned for a three month period over an area ranging from
26 degrees to 35 degrees north latitude, and for two months in
areas north of 35 degrees and from 24.5 degrees to 26 degrees.
</P>
<P>
China introduced the overall summer fishing ban in 1995. The
two month ban in effect in each of the past three years has helped
protect the natural habitat for fry. The ban has also helped
increase the size range of major fish species, such as hairtail,
and has at the same time improved offshore output figures.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has pledged to adopt a long-term ban,
and will introduce various other measure to protect marine
resources, including limiting the number of the size of fishing
fleet and controlling the intensity related activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0172 </DOCNO>
