<HEADLINE> EU, S. Africa to Reach Free Trade Deal: British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British
Secretary for Trade and Industry Peter Mandelson said that a free
trade deal between South Africa and the European Union (EU) could
be reached later this week.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the EU and South Africa, which began in
1994, had "gone too slowly in our view", local daily the Star
Tuesday quoted Mandelson as reporting.
</P>
<P>
He said the pact could be reached this week because a "great
deal" had been achieved although some issues still had to be
resolved. He did not specify what problems remained unsolved
between the EU and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It was generally believed free trade of agricultural products
between the two side has been focused in the negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson's visit coincided with the start of the first
British-South African partnership week trade exhibition in
Johannesburg Monday.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent flurry of unfavorable reports about
South Africa's economic policies, Mandelson expressed
disagreement over Wall Street Journal Europe's report that South
Africa was implementing "inconsistent economic policies".
</P>
<P>
"I don't accept the analysis," said Mandelson, describing the
report as "excessively pessimistic".
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa had sound economic fundamentals, which
would result in economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
