<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Three World Records, Sweeps Four Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China broke three world
records and swept the all four titles after the last disciplne of
cross-country race Tuesday at the 46th Military Pentathlon World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
China's Wang Lianying, 29, bettered the previous world record
of 5,420.4 points set by herself in 1996 with 5,434, winning the
women's individual for the fifth time in a row.
</P>
<P>
Wang also paced her teammates in top four of the overall
standings that ensured the Chinese to retain the women's team
trophy, the Challenge Cup, with a world record-beating 15,979.2
points.
</P>
<P>
The new record is 0.2 point more than the previous one set by
the Democratic Peoples' Republic of Korea last year.
</P>
<P>
The China's men's pentathletes created the day's third world
record of 22,052.5 points, 75.9 points better than their own
mark set in 1996 en route to winning the Debrus Cup, the team
title.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Li Zhong, who was the first runner to hit the tape in
the cross-country, led a 1-2-3 finish in the men's individual
standings, with Yang Chunyi second and Zhao Min third.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Carlos Silva of Brazil finished fourth in
the overall as his country won the silver medal in the men's team.
</P>
<P>
Ilova Lubane of Latvia also completed the record-shattering
spree with the day's fourth world record, breaking the women's
cross-country world record of 14 minutes 09.0 seconds set by
Firing Hanne of Norway in 1993, with a time of 14:02.3.
</P>
<P>
But the Latvian finished only 12th on the final table.
</P>
<P>
The last gold medal of the championships will be handed out on
Wednesday in the obstacles relay race, with China still the hot
favorite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
