<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Approves Funding for Hybrid Rice Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
recently approved a 10-million-yuan research grant for Yuan
Longping, the Father of Hybrid Rice, according to the State
Hybrid Rice Engineering and Research Center (SHRERC).
</P>
<P>
Yuan, a member of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, has for
many years conducted extensive research related to the cultivation
of new strains of hybrid rice. He introduced new techniques for
cultivating hybrid rice in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The cultivation of high-yielding rice has been a global
priority over the years. Estimates call for China to plant seven
million ha of hybrid rice annually beginning early next century,
with the annual rice output expected to grow by some 15 billion kg
per year.
</P>
<P>
Three experimental areas using the new method yielded an
average of 13,260 kg per ha in 1997, up 3,375 kg on the output for
other high quality varieties. The quality of Yuan's hybrid rice
equaled second-level quality rice in terms of resistance to two
or more pests.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural research organizations from east China's Jiangsu
province, Liaoning Province in the north and Guangdong Province in
the south are engaged in related research and joined the center
in forming a national cooperative network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
