<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Irish Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
today expressed China's appreciation of the Irish government's
positive efforts to develop Sino-Irish ties and said the nation is
fully prepared to join the Irish side in promoting cooperation in
various fields and elevating bilateral relations to a new high.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks during a meeting with visiting Irish
Prime Minister Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
Jiang thanked Ahern for conveying expressions of sympathy and
condolences Irish President Mary Mcaleese voiced for Chinese flood
victims, and briefed his guests on recent flood-control efforts.
</P>
<P>
"China treasures its long-term, stable and friendly cooperative
relations with Ireland, " said Jiang, adding that next year will
be the 20th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties
between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed to the dramatic changes which have taken place in
the world over the past two decades and noted that Sino-Irish ties
have enjoyed great progress which has included expanded bilateral
exchanges and cooperation in the political, economic and trade
arenas, as well as enhanced mutual understanding and friendship
between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The Irish foreign minister and a number of parliamentary
leaders visited China during the first half of this year, said
Jiang, adding that extensive contacts have been and will be
conducive to increasing mutual understanding and furthering
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president noted the quite different historical and
cultural backgrounds and ideologies of the two nations, but
pointed out that cooperation can be strengthened even further so
long as they follow the principle of mutual respect and mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
Jiang recounted his visit to an Irish special economic zone in
1980 and expressed appreciation of the great importance Ireland
attaches to attracting foreign investment and advanced technology
needed to accelerate its national economy over the past few
decades.
</P>
<P>
Ahern cited great pleasure at having the opportunity to
personally view China's great achievements.
</P>
<P>
He praised the unremitting efforts Chinese civilians and
armymen made to keep flood losses at an absolute minimum.
</P>
<P>
Ahern is leading a delegation of 30-odd Irish business
representatives. The Irish leader said that discussions of
political issues will be accompanied by in-depth discussions of
economic and trade issues. He said Ireland hopes to join China in
strengthening bilateral exchanges and cooperation in related
fields and to further develop long-term close relations between
the two nations.
</P>
<P>
He said Ireland is also willing to promote the cooperation
between the European Union and China.
</P>
<P>
Ahern briefed Jiang on the domestic and social situations in
Ireland and the peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Jiang reaffirmed China's support for peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Ahern arrived Monday as guest of Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
