<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Budget Deficit Within Yearly Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's budget spending
exceeded revenues by 35 percent in August, keeping the country
still on track to meet its yearly target of 42 percent, the Daily
Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the Finance Ministry's monthly report issued
on Monday as saying that the government collected 222.5 million
U.S. dollars last month and spent 337 million dollars, of which
103.3 million dollars went toward debt servicing.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, revenues reached 1.98
billion dollars and expenditure amounted to 3.15 billion dollars,
resulting in a deficit of 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
A fall in debt servicing was the main reason behind the drop in
expenditure in August, said an official of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"Interest payments fell because fewer treasury bills
accumulated and matured. That was the case in July," the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has a total of 15.5 billion dollars debt at the end of
June, of which nearly 70 percent are high interest rate internal
paper.
</P>
<P>
The official did not explain how the government collected the
money last month but said that customs and income and property
taxes accounted for approximately 80 percent of public revenue.
</P>
<P>
He expected revenues to pick up by the end of the year because
some income tax payments had been rescheduled and people tended to
settle their property taxes during the last month of the year.
</P>
<P>
Fuad Sinyoura, minister of state for financial affairs, said
that although spending and revenues did not distribute evenly every
month, the budget deficit should finish the year at below 42
percent.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, which is recovering from a 15-year devastating civil
war, saw a worst economic performance last year with the budget
deficit reaching a record high of 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government vowed to harness the ballooning deficit this
year by adopting an austerity financial policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
