<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Two U.S. intelligence agencies Monday accused
Russian firms of exporting weapons technology and the country
still being able to revive its once massive chemical and
biological warfare capability.
</P>
<P>
Russia maintains the basic building blocks of the former Soviet
Union's chemical and biological weapons capability, the Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA) and Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA)
told lawmakers. (US-Russia-Chemical Warfare)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- At least three supporters of Albania's opposition
leader Sali Berisha were killed and 14 others wounded Monday when
government forces launched a counterattack to calm down an
anti-government protest, police said.
</P>
<P>
The protest, prompted by the weekend assassination of the
popular opposition leader Azem Hajdari, touched off a wild day of
unrest in the capital. (Albania-Unrest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Richard Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM), said here Monday that Iraq must be
cooperative with it on the issue of Iraqi weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after meeting Swedish Foreign
Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen, he said Iraq should first tell what
kind of weapons it possesses and then where they are stored. He
added inspections on Iraq's missiles and chemical weapons could
end in months if the Iraqi government provides the commission with
needed information and documents. (Sweden-Iraq-Butler)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- A vehicle carrying three Canadian diplomatic
observers hit a mine and overturned in western Kosovo on Monday,
leaving a woman interpreter injured.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Pristina news center said the incident
happened in the Drenica area south of the village of Likovac,
while the three-member team was heading for Donje Obrinje, a
village dominated by ethnic Albanian gunmen of the separatist
"Kosovo Liberation Army". (Canada-Kosovo-Explosion) 
</P>
