<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deactivated Nuclear Energy Base Attracts Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The world's first deactivated
nuclear energy development base on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau in
northwest China has been transformed into a tourist attraction and
a haven for overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
A recent Sino-U.S. agreement calls for the construction of a
thermal power plant at the former nuclear base in Xihai Township
located in the Haibei Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture, Qinghai
Province. The plant will be the first overseas-funded project in
the township which developed China's first atomic and hydrogen
bombs.
</P>
<P>
Panda Energy International Inc. of the United States, the
overseas partner, will provide 90 percent of the 250 million US
dollars financing for the new thermal power plant with an annual
generating capacity of 250,000 kw.
</P>
<P>
The prefectural government's contribution to the project will
include the former No. 7 plant at the facility.
</P>
<P>
"Abundant coal reserves and the highly efficient government
offered by the so-called 'China Nuclear Town' greatly enhance
prospects for the thermal power plant," according to Panda Vice
President Todd Carter.
</P>
<P>
Panda has invested heavily in China, with major projects
including the gigantic Gezhouba Hydro-Electric Power Station in
central China's Hubei Province and a thermal power plant in
Tangshan of north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The central government formally granted the local government
control of the deactivated facility in 1995, following an eight
year environmental cleanup program. Xihai Township was established
and named as the seat of the prefectural government.
</P>
<P>
Facilities covering 100,000 sq.m. have been transformed into
office buildings, residential areas, hotels, stores, schools and
factories. Song birds, pastures filled with cows and sheep, stands
of trees and patches of flowers can be found throughout the
township.
</P>
<P>
Both domestic and foreign investors have expressed interest in
remaining buildings with total floor space of well over 560,000
sq.m., including workshops covering 220,000 square meters. The
township features a relatively well-developed infrastructure
system which includes highway and railway networks.
</P>
<P>
The local government has introduced preferential land-use and
taxation policies to attract overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Local officials reported that negotiations for an electrolysis
aluminum project involving Japanese and Singaporean interests are
entering a crucial stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
