<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Injured in Soccer Fans' Clash in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 100 persons including
10 policemen and five journalists were injured when rival groups
of agitated fans of two football teams clashed in southeastern
Bangladesh's Chittagong seaport on Monday, a local report said.
</P>
<P>
At least 50 vehicles were damaged in the two-hour long clash
which spread from the Chittagong M.A. Aziz Stadium from 8:30 p.m.
local time, said the English-language Independent daily newspaper
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The clash occurred two minutes before the end of a match
between the Mohammedan Sporting Club and the Abhani Krjra Chakra,
two leading local soccer teams, when the Mohammedan equalized the
match from a corner kick, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The match ended with a 1-1 draw.
</P>
<P>
The agitated fans of both the clubs used lethal weapons,
exploded crackers and exchanged brickbats indiscriminately at the
stadium and the clash later spread to other areas. The police
lobbed tear gas shells and resorted to batons to disperse the
clashing groups.
</P>
<P>
The police allegedly resorted to batons at the press box, and
three photo journalists were seriously injured in the police
attack.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said the clash took place when the referee
canceled the goal scored by the Mohammedan and later restored it.
The linesman hoisted the flag for fault kick given from corner
point by a Mohammedan player. 
</P>
</TEXT>
