<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000 Palestinians Allowed into Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 Palestinians
were allowed to enter Israel as of Tuesday morning as Israel eased
its closure of the West Bank and Gaza for the first time since it
killed two Palestinian fugitives last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,000 Palestinian laborers from the Gaza Strip and 2,000
from the West Bank were granted entry, in addition to another
3,000 merchants and businessmen, after Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai approved the easing Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The seal-off was imposed last Thursday night after Hamas
threatened to launch a series of terror attacks in retaliation
for the killing of two of its leaders - the brothers of Adel and
Imad Awadallah - by Israeli soldiers near Hebron. It was the
first full closure in 13 months.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that he had not set a date for the lifting of
the closure, since the Hamas threats had not tailed off yet. Some
military sources have indicated that the closure would remain in
effect till after the Jewish holidays which begin late this month.
</P>
<P>
The closure caused a direct loss of 4 million to 5 million
U.S. dollars every day to the Palestinian economy, and indirect
damage is double that amount and long-term damage is incalculable,
Nabil Shaath, minister for planning and international cooperation
of the Palestinian National Authority, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, however, said Israel is "not interested in using
closure as a means of punishment."
</P>
<P>
The easing of the closure follows a new plan prepared by the
Israeli government to allow some Palestinians to work under
certain conditions. Some 30,000 Palestinians are registered to
participate in the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reaffirms Stability of Renminbi Exchange Rate (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange said here today that China is
confident and capable of maintaining the stability of its
currency, the Renminbi (RMB) yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis, especially wide fluctuations in the
Japanese yen over the past few months, have impacted China's
economic growth, said the official, adding that a series of
measures the Chinese government introduced to increase exports and
attract overseas investment have yielded good results.
</P>
<P>
China had a favorable trade balance of 31.38 billion
U.S. dollars for the first eight months of this year, according to
the official. He said the volume of direct overseas investment for
the first seven months hit 23.9 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserves stand at more than 140
billion U.S. dollars, excluding foreign exchange held by Chinese
financial institutions, businesses and individuals.
</P>
<P>
The volume leaves ample room for regulating demand and supply
for foreign exchange, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government recently announced a decision to issue
100 billion yuan in state treasury bonds to promote infrastructure
construction. The goal of the move centers on expanding domestic
demand to counteract declining exports and ensuring fulfillment of
the annual economic growth target of eight percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that ensuring the stability of the yuan will not only
offset economic deterioration in Asia and the world as a whole,
but will also maintain market confidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
