<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Remove Impediments for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- All the government
departments dealing with would-be investors in Zambia's tourism
sector should remove bureaucratic impediments, urged a local
senior tourism official.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Permanent secretary Romance Sampa said this in a speech at
the start of one-day "Tourism Investor Roadmap Workshop" in Lusaka
Monday, Times of Zambia reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Time has come for all government agents registering investors
in the tourism industry to remove all unnecessary bureaucratic
procedures, Sampa said.
</P>
<P>
He noted as much as the private sector would like to abide by laws
and regulations pertaining to the country, they would also like a
simplified operating system to avoid wasting time and money.
</P>
<P>
He challenged workshop participants including those from the
Investment Center, police, civil aviation and tourism councils to
come up with solutions for the effective implementation of a
mechanism that would see the country's tourism industry grow.
</P>
<P>
The permanent secretary also disclosed that the National Parks and
Wildlife Services has been turned into a statutory autonomous
organization which would improve the management and conservations of
wildlife resources.
</P>
<P>
He said other legislative changes were in progress to allow for
streamlined licensing and investment procedures in the industry.
</P>
<P>
Despite the various tourist attraction areas in Zambia which
have a variety of offers, inflow of tourists has not been very
encouraging due to insufficient investment.
</P>
<P>
The country received only 340,000 foreign tourists in 1997 and
earned about 75.5 million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
