<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Company to Build New Bridge in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China State Construction
Engineering Corporation will build the Rama 8 Bridge across the
Chao Phraya River running through Bangkok under a contract signed
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, a royal-initiated project, has got the approval of
the Thai cabinet with a total budget of 31.7 billion baht (about
800 million U.S. dollars), of which 70 percent will be subsidized
by the government.
</P>
<P>
The main structure of the bridge will be built by the Chinese
company while its attached parts are to be constructed by Thai,
Swiss, Canadian and British companies.
</P>
<P>
Bhichit Rattakul, governor of Bangkok and ambassadors from
China, Britain, Canada and Switzerland were present at the
contract signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, after completion in two years, will ease the
traffic congestion in Bangkok, provide a better look for Thailand
and create job opportunities for local communities.
</P>
<P>
The bridge was granted the name by Thailand's King Bhumibol
Adulyadej in commemoration of his elder brother King Ananda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Support Urged for African Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The African insurance
industry lacks political support to match global competition,
reinsurance seminar has noted.
</P>
<P>
Bakary Kamara, Chief of the African Reinsurance Corporation,
said Africa's insurance landscape needed re-adjustment and the
adaptation of the guiding framework.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that insurance legislation must be refashioned
and adapted to the current world economic environment to which
Africa cannot afford to be just a spectator," Kamara was quoted

by Tuesday's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Proper legislation by governments and the
professional initiative of insurance practitioners were important
in promoting the industry, Kamara said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said obstacles in exchange restrictions should be removed
to give commercial transactions the required latitude.
</P>
<P>
He said legislation drawn up to cover wide and diversified
areas such as communication would be incomplete without giving a
prominent place to the exigencies of reinsurances security.
</P>
<P>
"In the very near future, like certain markets of South Asia,
Africa would require that all reinsurers willing to write
business within its territories should undergo a security test
and rating conducted by a specialized independent firm," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said economic depression should not become a scapegoat
for African countries, as economic recession had affected the
whole world, yet developed countries were able to pull the
industry together.
</P>
<P>
"The continent is still standing on the quay, watching as the
train of economic development speeds past, while it wallows in
the grip of poverty, misery and diseases," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that economic non-performance had a major
impact on the African insurance industry and, consequently, on
the organizational structure of the markets.
</P>
<P>
Kamara attributed the poor performance to political instability
which, he said, affected economic productivity and growth.
</P>
<P>
Sixty senior insurance managers from more than 40 African
countries attended the five-day seminar starting Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
