<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The sell-off of a number of ailing state-run companies
within the privatization program has made net profits of 2.4
billion pounds (about 706 million U.S. dollars), Egyptian Minister
of Public Enterprises Atef Ebeid said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Before being privatized, these companies had accumulated losses
of 42 million pounds (about 12.5 million dollars), Atef told a
seminar labeled "Companies on Privatization Program," organized by
the American Chamber of Commerce in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The government had 314 state companies on the privatization
scheme, 113 of which were already sold. About 60 others were
currently put for sale, while the rest were in the pipeline for
1999.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian government will pick up its talks with the
Iraqi authorities to resume a project which aims at diverting
water from Iraq to Jordan, Minister of Water and Irrigation Hani
Malki said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The water from Iraq will be used to feed the northern part of
Jordan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides initiated the project in 1979 but later were forced
to delay it due to regional instability, he added.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- At present a total of 10,100 industrial projects are
under construction throughout Iran, local daily Tehran Times
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Statistic Department of Industries Ministry
Moqtada Rawanbakhsh said that out of the total, some 5,000
projects were at the final phase of operation and would create
190,000 job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government will call for tenders in the
coming weeks for three dams to be constructed in the western side
of the kingdom, Minister of Water and Irrigation Hani Malki said.
</P>
<P>
The dams will be used to provide water for the eastern coast of
the Dead Sea and the industrial sites in the Jordan Valley, he
added. 
</P>
