<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reaffirms Stability of Renminbi Exchange Rate (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman explained China's reasons for maintaining the
stability of its currency by noting that devaluating the currency
would neither increase exports, nor boost economic growth. He
said devaluation would most likely have a negative effect.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the yuan would play a minimal role in boosting
exports sine over half of materials for exports processing with
supplied parts are imported from abroad. Secondly, devaluation of
the yuan would lead to rising prices for imported materials and in
turn increase production costs for Chinese enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The principal reason for the slowdown in China's export centers
on declining imports from Southeast Asia, Japan and the Republic
of Korea. Devaluation of the yuan would most likely fail to
stimulate imports from Asian countries, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Facts clearly show that the currencies of some southeast Asian
nations have been devalued by as much as 50 percent. However,
devaluations failed to promote export and economic growth in said
nations, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the yuan would offer no benefits to China's
economic and political development. While devaluation might
possibly stimulate exports in the short-term, it would fall far
short of raising the technical quality of products and services.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the yuan would be detrimental to the long-term
balance of revenues and expenditures and would dampen the
confidence of overseas investors or, in fact, drive some investors
away. It would also increase the debt levels of Chinese
enterprises and harm the balance of foreign exchange under current
accounts.
</P>
<P>
Devaluation of the yuan would also spark inflation and lead to
higher interest rates and reductions in monetary assets, as well
as drops in the disposable income of Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, it is more important to maintain the stability of
the yuan and ensure a sound economic and financial environment
than it is to increase exports by devaluing the yuan. (moire)

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mary Robinson: China Visit "Broke New Ground" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- United Nations high
commissioner for human rights Mary Robinson said that her China
visit not only "accomplished pre-set goals" but also "broke new
ground" in international cooperation for human rights.
</P>
<P>
She made the remark at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Vice Premier Qian Qichen met
with her yesterday. During her ten-day tour she also attended
academic activities on human rights in Beijing and visited
Shanghai and the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
She said the tour "opened up a channel for constructive
dialogue and cooperation" and her office and relevant Chinese
departments also "agreed on follow-up actions."
</P>
<P>
As the first U.N. human rights high commissioner ever to visit
China, she said she made the journey to "hear and listen" to the
life of the Chinese people and the efforts made by the government
to promote and protect human rights.
</P>
<P>
She told reporters that she got the message from Vice Premier
Qian that China will sign a covenant on civil and political rights
next month.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has already signed the international
covenant on economic, social and cultural rights, and this
document is to be ratified by the National People's Congress,
China's law-making body, after examination.
</P>
<P>
Her office and China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs signed a
Memorandum of Intent on a technical cooperation program between
her office and the ministry. She said that the two sides will
undertake programs to train lawyers and judges and carry out human
rights education. "Some suggestions have already gotten response
from the Chinese side," she said.
</P>
<P>
On her impression of Tibet, Robinson said the autonomous region
is a "beautiful and special place," adding that the trip made her
aware of the commitment from the central government to promote
economic development and safeguard the region's cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the China visit deepened her understanding of
the country and that she would like to return some day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
