<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reaffirms Stability of Renminbi Exchange Rate (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman addressed questions concerning the stability of
the Chinese currency and the country's economic prospects by
noting that the financial crisis in Asia has had some impact on
China's economic growth over the past year.
</P>
<P>
He said the impact will quite likely grow as the crisis
deteriorates and spreads to wider areas.
</P>
<P>
China's refusal to devaluate the yuan has already caused the
country to incur losses in terms of efforts to stabilize the
regional and, in fact, the global economy.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that China, with a population of 1.2
billion, has a vast domestic market and the economic strength to
overcome the negative impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the steadfast decision to protect the yuan from
devaluating was made on the basis of the country's domestic
economic conditions," according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese citizens are fully confident of the
strength of country's currency, and noted that China is the only
Asian country currently able to attract large amount of long-term
overseas investment. He also noted that strict control systems
govern the use of China's over 140 billion U.S. dollars in foreign
exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed total confidence in the continuing
stability of the yuan and the nation's ability to maintain the
momentum of rapid, healthy and sustainable growth of the national
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
