<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
Cairo -- Egypt has embarked on an ambitious plan to tap its
abundant sources of unconventional energy in the coming century,
the Egyptian Gazette reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an Energy Conference in Houston in the U.S.,
Egyptian Minister of Energy and Power Maher Abaza said Egypt
applied a long-term plan to produce 6,000 megawatt from
wind-operated plants.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the power sector was currently executing two power
projects which would produce 4,000 megawatt from solar energy and
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference entitled "Challenges and Options,"
brings together 7,000 representatives from 160 countries to
discuss 200 research papers on the future of energy in the world.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- German and Jordanian officials here Monday signed an
agreement to remit 20 million Deutsch marks (about 12 million
U.S. dollars) of debts that Jordan owes, Jordan's official news
agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The money is part of a total 40 million marks (about 24
million dollars) of debts that Jordan should repay to Germany
now.
</P>
<P>
Germany agreed to remit half of the total debts and change the
other half into investments in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh said here
on Monday that oil prices would increase gradually at the world
markets.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh made the remark on the sidelines of the 9th seminar on
oil, gas and petrochemicals opened here on Monday. However, he did
not give reasons for his prediction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
