<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khamenei Orders Iran's Armed Forces on Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei Tuesday ordered the armed forces to be
alert to follow the developments in Afghanistan, the official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
"All officials and those in charge of affairs of the country,
including the armed forces, must be ready for speedy, timely and
decisive implementation of whatever decisions the senior political
and security authorities deem necessary and right for the
country," Khamenei said.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with senior commanders of the Islamic
Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC), he said that all the military
apparatus, the security and press establishments should maintain
full readiness to protect interests of the country and fulfill
their humanitarian obligations.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei's call came as tensions between Iran and Afghan
Taliban militia built up after nine Iranian diplomats were killed
in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
For weeks, Iran has claimed that the Taliban held 70 Iranians,
including 11 diplomats and a journalist after taking over the city
of Mazar-e-Sharif, a stronghold of the opposition forces on August
8.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which had denied knowledge of those people
missing, confirmed last Thursday that its men killed nine of the
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Iran has massed a massive force near the Afghan border
following the diplomats incident for military exercises, widely
seen as warning to the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, a student militia, ousted President Burhanuddin
Rabbani and his government in 1996 after storming into capital
Kabul and has now won control over 90 percent of the country.
</P>
<P>
Fightings between the Taliban and opposition Northern Alliance
led by Rabbani are continuing.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that the situation in Afghanistan was highly
crucial from various aspects.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan issue is a humanitarian concern for Iranians who
feel sympathy for the Afghan people, he said, "from the Islamic
aspect, we have an obligation, from the political and national
aspect, we should also avert any danger for the nation and the
country."
</P>
<P>
The IRGC Monday night issued a statement, declaring its
readiness to "help the oppressed Afghan people" after Khamenei
called on Islamic states to prevent the Taliban from slaughtering
the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the forces under the IRGC command and
the Basij (volunteer) forces were fully prepared to follow the
order of Khamenei, who is commander-in-chief of the armed forces,
and to "help the Afghan people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
