<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents in Wellington Hit 10-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Both alcohol- and speed-
related traffic accidents in the Wellington region of New Zealand
hit
a 10-year low last year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued here Tuesday by the Wellington
region
of the Land Transport Safety Authority of New Zealand, there were
112
drink-driving and 192 speed-related crashes in the region, the
lowest
numbers in 10 years, compared with 142 and 252 in 1996
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The report said 990 people were injured or killed on the
region's
roads last year, compared with 1,068 in 1996. Wellington City
recorded the largest drop last year with 355 crashes, down 67 on
1996.
</P>
<P>
But, there were 25 road deaths in the Wellington region,
compared
with 24 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of pedestrians and motorcyclists injured in road
accidents in the Wellington region was still of concern. Of the
134
pedestrians injured last year, 65 were in Wellington City. There
were
127 motorcyclists injured in crashes last year, up from 118 in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The report said the road crashes in the Wellington region were
estimated to cost the country 239 million NZ dollars (121 million
U.S.
dollars) last year, which included accident rehabilitation and
compensation insurance and hospital costs, emergency services and
loss of earnings for those injured.
</P>
<P>
The declining road toll was attributed to increasing public
awareness about alcohol and speed and traffic improvements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
