<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scarce Baht Discourages Speculators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The relative scarcity of the
baht in offshore markets has helped reduce the ability of foreign
speculators to attack the Thai currency even when regional markets
are volatile.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Bank of Thailand said on Tuesday that
speculators would be discouraged in betting against the baht given
the high swap premiums in the offshore market.
</P>
<P>
While overnight swap rates in the local and offshore markets
traded quite closely together, there was a spread of 4 to 5
percent for longer-term maturities, Kiettisak Meecharoen,
assistant bank governor, told the press.
</P>
<P>
The baht traded at 40.77/40.84 to the U.S. dollar on Monday.
The central bank's weighted reference rate for last Friday's rate
was 40.811.
</P>
<P>
Close management of baht supply in the local money market has
also helped stabilize exchange rates. Regulators were able to
manage supply through buying and selling government bonds in the
repurchase market, Kiettisak said.
</P>
<P>
Onshore one-month swap premiums on Tuesday were quoted at 5/10
satang (100 satang equals one baht), compared with 20/26 in
offshore trade, while overnight interbank rates were quoted at 8
percent and the central bank's overnight repurchase rate was 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The last of Thailand's offshore swap obligations would be
settled by the end of this week, according to the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Some 9 billion dollars in forward swap obligations with local
banks will be maintained by the central bank, primarily to manage
liquidity in the market.
</P>
<P>
Kiettisak said swaps with onshore counterparties would be
reduced next year, when the repurchase market and open market
operations become the main policy instrument for managing market
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
"The central bank has run down total swap obligations from 18
billion dollars outstanding at the beginning of the year. By doing
so, the baht has been pulled back into the onshore market," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The bank took out more than 23.4 billion dollars in swap
obligations as part of its failed defense of the baht last year.
The depletion of foreign reserves ultimately forced the government
to accept assistance from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Kiettisak said he believed U.S. interest rates would decline,
easing pressure on global rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
