<HEADLINE> Kenyans to Die Younger: U.N. Official  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The life expectancy of
Kenyans is expected to drop from 60 to 40 years by 2000 if the
U.N. official warns.
</P>
<P>
The poverty and deprivation levels are also set to go up if
the Kenyan government does not show the will to sort out its
economic and political problems, said Fredric Lyons, the
Kenyan representative of U.N. Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
Lyons told a workshop at Kenyan coastal city Mombasa that the
1998 U.N. Human Development Index showed Kenya had dropped from
position 134 to 137, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to play a greater role in creating
more awareness on the HIV/AIDS infections.
</P>
<P>
Although the Kenyan government had done a lot in primary
health care and general development of the health sector, the
results were now being overshadowed by high level of AIDS, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS had already killed 230,000 Kenyans by the end of
1997 while more than 1.3 million are said to be HIV-positive in
the eastern African country. It is estimated that about one

million Kenyans may die of AIDS by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
