<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 07:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Lebanon National Orchestra to Be Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon government has issued
a decree, officially approving the launch of the country's first
national orchestra, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited decree was published in the latest Official
Gazette, finally allowing the Conservatoire Superieur de la
Musique to start working to form an orchestra "in keeping with
International standards."
</P>
<P>
"The orchestra will be made up of between 75 and 90 musicians
and if things proceed as planned, it will hold its first concert
in the autumn of next year," said Walid Gholmieh, chairman of the
Conservatoire.
</P>
<P>
"We now have 35 Lebanese musicians who fit the international
criteria for symphony orchestras and the rest will be foreigners
for the time being," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we'll try to benefit from their experience and ask them to
teach at the Conservatoire until we can form a truly national
orchestra comprising of only Lebanese musicians," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gholmieh refused to disclose how much money had been allotted
by the government for the project, saying: "I don't want to hear
some people saying that setting up an orchestra isn't a priority
in Lebanon right now and criticizing spending money on this
cultural project."
</P>
<P>
The decree carried the signatures of President Elias Hrawi,
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Minister of Culture Fawzi Hobeish.
</P>
<P>
"This means the three statesmen have thrown their weight behind
the project," the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
"We've been calling for official support for the project for
years and years." he added.
</P>
<P>
The orchestra will focus on performing classical music works
composed by Lebanese and famous foreign composers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
