<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Foreign Exchange Reserves Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's foreign exchange
reserves rose to 1.824 billion U.S. dollars on September 10 from
1.6 billion dollars in August despite disruptions in exports
caused by the severe deluge, The Financial Express daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The rise in foreign exchange reserves was attributed to inflow
of nearly 166 million dollars worth of aid in cash and kind from
the foreign donors for emergency relief and post-flood
rehabilitation, the report quoted central bank sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Immediate pressure on the foreign exchange reserves was
unlikely because the initial disruptions in exports following the
snapping of roads and rail links were averted through arranging a
specially chartered aircraft from the Thai Airways, they said.
</P>
<P>
The need for food imports due to crop losses caused by the
flood would not harm the balance of payments situation as half of
an estimated two million tons in flood-caused food shortage was
expected to be met from foreign assistance, they added.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program has already pledged 355,000 tons of
foodgrain for flood-hit Bangladesh in addition to the 550,000 tons
it pledged earlier to meet the country's usual annual food deficit
of two million tons, while the United States and several others
have so far pledged more than 500,000 tons of foodgrain.
</P>
<P>
Besides, both the government and private sectors were preparing
to import foods to meet the resultant deficit, which could put
some pressure on the foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
But the pressure could be minimum as the International Monetary
Fund might help Bangladesh under an emergency assistance facility
to improve its balance of payments situation, they said.
</P>
<P>
The over-two-month-long floods have so far killed more than 800
people, displaced nearly 30 million others and caused severe
damage to crops, properties and infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
