<HEADLINE> World Champion Wang to Defend Her Title Next Year, Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China's five-time champion
Wang Lianying will defend her title at next year's Military
Pentathlon World Championships before her retirement, coach Wu
Jianzhu said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"As far as her health concerned, Wang should retire after
next championships in Croatia in August, 1999," Wu told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who broke her own world record to win her straight fifth
champion earlier in the day, said, "I will compete in next year's
championships if my health allows."
</P>
<P>
But she did not say whether she will quit after that.
</P>
<P>
Wu said Wang has some problem in her heart, which has beening
hindered her normal training.
</P>
<P>
Wang won the consecutive fifth time crown with a new world
record and is believed to retain the trophy next August if she
could make the tour to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
"No one is expected to inherit Wang's legend in the
competition by now, " Wu said. "But we'll keep our overwhelming
strength because we've a strong backup team."
</P>
<P>
Chinese pentathletes have won all but one titles at the
current five events championships. They are also favored to take
the last gold in the obstacles relay races on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
