<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Trade Fair Generates Widespread Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The 8-day Second Trade Fair
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC)
which ends here Tuesday evening has generated widespread interest
and business inquiries for the majority of exhibitors, Trade Fair
sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
While a large number of inquiries were made by prospective
buyers, several exhibitors had also been approached for joint
ventures, the sources told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Nepali exhibitors had received positive inquiries from Sri
Lankan and other buyers for lentils, liquor, candy, fruit juices,
jute products, herbal oil and flooring material. Meanwhile, there
were several inquiries from Sri Lankan companies for the export of
herbal oil and for the establishment of joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Bhutan had also received several inquiries from Sri Lankan
businessmen for chip board, canned fruits, jams and juices. About
10 Sri Lankan companies and two from Iran and Canada each had made
positive inquiries from Bhutan Agro Industries Ltd., the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The Maldives which was represented only by its Tourism
Promotion Board said they had several inquiries for tuna fishing
from Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is confident that its extruded aluminum products and
anodized profiles received large orders as a result of
participating at the fair.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan companies have also had their share of positive
inquiries. A software engineering firm had inquiries about its
accounting and banking software packages.
</P>
<P>
General Foods had encouraging inquiries from India and Pakistan
. The two countries were highly interested in Sri Lanka's boilers,
bearings, packaging, pumps, compressors, machinery, wood work, and
bottle manufacturing during the fair.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistani textile manufacturer was interested in exporting
textiles to Sri Lanka while Pakistan's Macto Rice Processing
company had received large orders for its Basmathi rice in Sri
Lanka, a Sri Lankan businessman said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300 stalls at the fair from the seven SAARC
member countries -- Bangladesh, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The 8-day fair was opened last Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
