<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Killed in Albanian Unrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- At least three supporters of
Albania's opposition leader Sali Berisha were killed and 14 others
wounded Monday when government forces launched a counterattack to
calm down an anti-government protest, police said.
</P>
<P>
The protest, prompted by the weekend assassination of the
popular opposition leader Azem Hajdari, touched off a wild day of
unrest in the capital Tirana.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of opposition supporters took to the streets,
gathering at Skanderbeg Square in the morning to mourn for
assassinated Hajdari.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, former president Sali Berisha repeated
allegations that Prime Minister Fatos Nano was responsible for
Hajdari's death. He urged Nano to step down.
</P>
<P>
Shooting broke out after mourners carried Hajdari's body to
Nano's office following the service at Skanderbeg Square.
</P>
<P>
Armed rioters shot at and bombed Nano's office. Automatic
weapons fire reportedly ripped through the city.
</P>
<P>
Rioters also seized tanks from the guards, and surrounded
national TV stations. Some expensive shops were looted. Masked
men at checkpoints stopped cars heading out of the city, robbing
drivers and occupants, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Armed vehicles and police forces were sent in to stop the
turbulence, termed by Nano as a coup d'etat.
</P>
<P>
Government forces soon regained control of seized key
facilities: Parliament, the state television and radio building
and Nano's office, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Rexhep Meidani condemned the chaos in a TV
speech, accusing "armed groups" of adopting violence to achieve
their purpose. He vowed to punish those behind the scene in line
with the law.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the country's largest ruling party, the
Socialist Party of Albania, was discussing solutions to the
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
The president was consulting political parties in search of a
solution, including forming a new government possibly without
Nano, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed over the prospect of further instability, the United
Sates and the European Union appealed for calm, fearful the
turmoil could topple Albania's elected government and spread
elsewhere in the Balkans, including neighboring Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, Berisha, despise severe criticism from international
leaders and threatened arrest by the government, has called for
another rally Tuesday at the same site where the protest was held
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
