<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Italy's major car maker Fiat plans to introduce
its complete range of "Palio 178" vehicles in India and the first
car from this range is expected to be launched next year, company
sources said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The "Palio" family consists of a Hatchback, the Siena Saloon
and the weekend station wagon.
</P>
<P>
As part of its globalization plans, Fiat would bring its 30 to
40 component manufacturers to India to source ancillary products
for the car project. Fiat is also considering manufacturing the
engines and transmission system locally, the sources said.
(India-Fiat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's Ministry of Manpower has admitted it has
little power to stem the increasing tide of unemployment in the
country because it has been forced to postpone many of its
development projects.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Manpower Fahmi Idris told legislators in a hearing
on Monday that many of his ministry's planned development projects
 had been postponed due to the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will be unable to reach its target of spending 50
percent of its 1998/99 fiscal year (beginning April) budget for
development projects because of the delays, he was quoted by the
Jakarta Post Tuesday as saying. (Indonesia-Unemployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- New York stocks rose sharply Monday, extending
Friday's rally, with the Dow Jones industrial average finishing
149.85 points higher at 7,945.35 after rising by as much as 243
points.
</P>
<P>
The Dow now sits above its 1998 starting point, 7,908.25. The
blue-chip barometer is still about 1,300 points, or 14 percent,
below the July 17's high.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators also extended Friday's rally. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 20.66 to 1,029.72, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 24.05 to 1,665.69.
(New York, Stocks Higher)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Monday called on
world economic powers "to act together to spur global economy" as
the world is facing "the biggest Challenge in a half century".
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Council on Foreign Relations in New York,
Clinton said the United States has an "inescapable obligation" to
help resolve the economic crisis affecting a growing number of
countries.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the fact that 30 percent of the U.S. economic
growth has been made due to trade with overseas countries since he
became president in 1992, Clinton said this is why "ordinary
Americans should care if Asia or Russia or South America are on
solid footing." (Clinton-World Economy) 
</P>
