<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Deeply Concerned over Regional Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The summit of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) which ended in
the early hours of Monday expressed deep concern over regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
In a 15-page communique which addresses a wide variety of
issues, the SADC summit noted with regret that the Great Lakes
region continue to pose serious security and refugees problems to
the regions of eastern, central and southern Africa,
</P>
<P>
It called on the international society to provide the
necessary diplomatic and logistical support toward efforts by
regional leaders to start a genuine process of negotiations in
the region, including Burundi and Rwanda, leading to a new
political dispensation guaranteeing liberty, democracy and
security for all citizens.
</P>
<P>
The summit expressed concern at the recent development in
Angola, and strongly condemned Jonas Savimbi's belligerent
non-compliance with the major provisions of the 1994 Lusaka
Protocol, which commits him to full demilitarization of his armed
forces, participation in a government of national unity and a
national defense force.
</P>
<P>
It urged member states to endure tight regulation and improved
control of airports and airspace to ensure effective
implementation of the U.N. sanctions against UNITA. The two-day
meeting undertook to adopt the necessary measures to ensure
compliance with decisions members have made through SADC, the
Organization of African Unity and U.N. resolutions on this
matter.
</P>
<P>
The communique called on the international community,
particularly countries and leaders who have an influence on
Savimbi to persuade the rebel movement to dedicate itself to the
path of peace and reconstruction in Angola as a matter of
urgency.
</P>
<P>
On the civil disturbances and loss of life following the
recent elections in Lesotho, the communique welcomed the mediation
initiative led by the South African government, which resulted in
the setting up of an SADC committee of experts to investigate the
validity or otherwise of allegations that the elections were
fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the heads of state and governments expressed deep
regret at the outbreak of war in the Democratic Republic of Congo
as a result of attempts by rebels and their backers to forcefully
remove the government of President Laurent Kabila from power.
</P>
<P>
The communique welcomed initiatives by SADC and its members
intended to assist in the restoration of peace, security and
stability in Congo (K), in particular the Victoria Falls and
Pretoria initiatives.
</P>
<P>
It reaffirmed the 14 members' call for an immediate cessation
of hostilities and commended the governments of Angola, Namibia
and Zimbabwe for timely providing troops to assist the government
and people of Congo in defeating the illegal attempt by rebels
and their allies to capture the capital Kinshasa, and other
strategic areas.
</P>
<P>
The summit emphasized the need for all political actors in
Congo to commit themselves to orderly and peaceful transition to
multi-party democracy, primarily through constructive
consultations and negotiations involving all stakeholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
