<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Faces Deficiency Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. armed forces are
facing deficiencies and the Pentagon is urging the White House and
Congress to take measures to assure that the services would have
the ability to protect the nation's interests in the next century,
said defense chief Monday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen has visited several bases
around the country in recent weeks to assess reports of problems
among the troops and planned to meet President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday and the nation's top military leaders to discuss the
military readiness.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking at all of the readiness issues.... We'll
continue to do so and examine ways in which whatever deficiencies
exist in our readiness can be addressed, and we'll be taking this
issue up with the president and Congress in the coming months,"
Cohen told reporters in Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
There were reports of pilot and spare parts shortages,
maintenance backlogs, recruiting deficits and morale problems in
the 1.4 million force recently, particularly as deployments have
lengthened in such places as Bosnia and the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Cohen admitted that the U.S. military is facing some strains,
particularly in the follow-on forces, troops who would act as a
second wave of support to front-line troops in a longer conflict.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the Navy and Air Force have recruiting shortfalls
and problems retaining more senior individuals under a booming
economy in the nation that offers attractive jobs.
</P>
<P>
The Army, he said, "has had to take money out of base
operations and infrastructure accounts to pay for readiness."
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon also told reporters last week
that "the first-to-deploy forces are well trained and ready and
able to do their job. There's some growing concern about the
follow-on forces."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the military leaders are ready to ask
Clinton to increase the planned defense budgets of 250 billion
U.S. dollars by as much as 10 billion to 15 billion dollars
annually to meet the needs in modernization of weapons, support
meaningful training and bases construction.
</P>
<P>
In the last years, Pentagon officials have suggested more base
closures to save money for weapons modernization, but
Republican-led Congress opposed the idea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
