<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Foreign Exchange Reserve Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Polish foreign exchange
reserve amounted to 26.765 billion U.S. dollars in the first seven
months of this year, an increase of almost one third over the end
of 1997, the Polish Press Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The increment of 6.095 billion U.S. dollars in the foreign
exchange reserve of the National Bank of Poland was attributed to
the continued rapid development of the national economy and
improvement of the investment environment in the country.
</P>
<P>
Large amounts of foreign capital withdrawn from Asian
countries, including non-performing investment, have flown into
Poland since the outbreak of the Southeast Asian financial crisis
last year, the news agency quoted bank statistics as saying.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Poland was able to take more than 5 billion
U.S. dollars in foreign investment in the first half of this year,
in addition to the 6.6 billion U.S. dollars taken last year.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to positive reasons, including the continued increase in
foreign exchange reserve, the Russian economic crisis has little
effect on the Polish economy, with its currency, zloty, stands
firm agaisnst the U.S. dollar at a rate of 3.58 to one on Monday,
0.22 higher than two weeks ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
