<HEADLINE> Myanmar Travel Show to Open in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A Myanmar Travel Show, aimed
at attracting more tourists from Thailand and promoting the
country's tourism industry, is due to open in Bangkok's Baiyoke
Sky Hotel Tuesday, The New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The two-day travel show, sponsored by the Myanmar Tourism
Development Committee, is participated in by 58 tourism industries
and two air services of the country with 1,186 entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
At the show, Myanmar entrepreneurs will seek means with their
Thai counterparts on increasing the number of tourists to the
country and will cooperate with Thai air services to extend
flights to Myanmar, offering special rates for package tours to
the tourist destinations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Thailand initiated an accord on cooperation in
tourism in July and the current travel show in Bangkok is the
second of its kind since the first one launched by Myanmar in
Singapore earlier that month.
</P>
<P>
Thailand plays a key role in supplying tourists to Myanmar
among its neighbors and ranks the second after Japan.
</P>
<P>
In 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March, a total of 7,331
Thais visited Myanmar out of more than 265,000 from 24 countries
and regions, according to the official Monthly Economic
Indicators.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's investment in Myanmar's hotels and tourism sector,
second only to Singapore, amounted to 200 million U.S. dollars in
eight projects at the end of June this year, out of the total
foreign investment of some 810 million dollars in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics also indicate that a total of 138,863
foreign tourists came to Myanmar in the first six months of this
year. Of them, 3,468 were Thais.
</P>
<P>
Despite the "Visit Myanmar Year" campaign launched in 1996,
Myanmar has received a smaller number of tourists in the past two
years. The country is taking measures to attract tourists in the
forthcoming open tourist season beginning October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
