<HEADLINE> UNSCOM: Iraq Must Be Cooperative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, chairman of
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), said here Monday that Iraq
must be cooperative with it on the issue of Iraqi weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after meeting Swedish Foreign
Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen, he said Iraq should first tell what
kind of weapons it possesses and then where they are stored.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here Monday on a two-day visit to Sweden,
currently chairman of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
He said inspections on Iraq's missiles and chemical weapons
could end in months if the Iraqi government provided the
commission with needed information and documents.
</P>
<P>
But if Iraq refused to do that, he said, he didn't know how
things would develop and that was a tragedy for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Security Council extended the eight-year
sanctions on Iraq indefinitely to punish it for its ban on UNSCOM
inspections of new storage sites of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has been tasked with eliminating Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction since Iraq's defeat in the 1991 Gulf War over Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Under U.N. resolutions, the oil embargo against Iraq can only
be lifted when UNSCOM and the International Atomic Energy Agency
certify that all Iraqi chemical, biological and nuclear weapons,
as well as long-range missiles have been destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
