<HEADLINE> Italy Prepares Possible Evacuation from Riot-Hit Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi on Monday advised the Defense Ministry to make all necessary
preparations for a swift evacuation of Italians from Albania
should the need arise in the wake of renewed violence.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said Prodi was closely following
the situation in Tirana and was in direct contact with the Italian
embassy in the Albanian capital.
</P>
<P>
Prodi has also spoken to Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani by
phone for first-hand and reliable information on prospects for
bringing the tension under control.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Foreign Ministry also released a statement urging
all sides in Albania to end the use of force and resort to
political means to overcome the crisis which, it stressed, was the
precondition for continuing international aid.
</P>
<P>
The statement called for early political consultations by
President Mejdani to clarify the positions of all sides and
resolve the crisis via a democratic process.
</P>
<P>
Italy is in contact with the United States and European
countries, as well as the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, the European Union, and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, in order to make a unified stand on the
Albania issue, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Senate Foreign Affairs Committee is moving a
scheduled session on the crisis in Albania to Tuesday, which will
also be attended by Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes were reported in Tirana for a second day
Monday. They were touched off by the weekend slaying of a leading
opposition deputy in parliament Azem Hajdari, a close associate of
former President Sali Berisha. 
</P>
