<HEADLINE> Philippine Car Makers Reject New Excise Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' car
assemblers have expressed opposition to the imposition of an
expanded excise tax on motor vehicles starting next year, the
Manila Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Many assemblers have warned of serious repercussions of the
measure on sales and prices that will further hurt the already
battered auto industry, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The industry is suffering from a very depressed market and if
the government will impose that (tax measure) we will suffer
more," Takeshi Fukuda, president of Toyota Motor Philippines Corp.
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Fukuda warned that the Philippines might follow the way of
Thailand whose motor car industry shrank by 70 to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Total industry sales of local assemblers have dropped 47
percent due to the lingering economic crisis and the credit
crunch.
</P>
<P>
Fukuda said that at present, the industry "is very thankful
that the government is not imposing that tax."
</P>
<P>
The government has planned to expand starting 1999 the coverage
of the excise tax on motor vehicles to include utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2 billion pesos (50 million dollars) in additional
revenues are expected to be raised by the government from this tax
measure. The tax is one of the nine revenue measures committed by
the Philippines to the International Monetary Fund (IMF). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
