<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Cuts Spending to Help Post-Flood Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 15 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region has asked all its administrative departments and
government institutions to cut their spending for the last four
months of this year, to help the reconstruction efforts in the
flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
While taking various measures to raise more flood-relief funds,
Inner Mongolia has ordered its administrative departments and
government institutions to reduce their budgets from now to the
end of the year by five percent.
</P>
<P>
The five-percent reduction will translate into an additional 10
million yuan -- which would otherwise be used to buy cars, launch
meetings and fund overseas travel -- for reconstruction in the
flood-stricken areas, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia has since this summer been ravaged by the worst
flooding in the century, which has resulted in grave economic
losses and property damage.
</P>
<P>
It is a major task of the regional government to fight the
floods, resume production and rebuild homes, the official
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
