<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-German Afforestation Program Benefits Helan Mountains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- China and Germany are
jointly establishing a tree shelterbelt on the eastern slopes of
the Helan Mountains in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The joint program calls for planting a shelterbelt covering
8,550 ha. by the year 2000, and enclosing 30,000 hectares of
forests in the moutains. Support projects such as irrigation
canals, technical consulting stations and roads are under
construction.
</P>
<P>
The forest coverage rate will be increased by five percent
following implementation of the project which was initiated in
1994 by the Sino-German Committee on Economy and Trade.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for the German partner to provide 12
million Deutsche marks, with the Chinese partner set to inject
62.19 million yuan (7.49 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Helan Mountains, located in the western section of the
Yinchuan Plain in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, block frigid
westerly winds and blowing sand from the deserts. The project will
be carried out in parts of seven counties and cities.
</P>
<P>
The massive afforestation project will not only improve the
environment, but will also provide more job opportunities for
local residents, according to local government sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
