<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Ravaged Areas Decide to Plant More Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Provinces and regions hit
with heavy summer flooding have vowed to plant more trees and
strengthen the protection of existing forests, according to the
State Forestry Administration.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China's Heilongjiang Province will start a dual-phase
natural forest conservation project later this year. The plan
calls for prohibiting logging in natural forests by the year 2000
and planting trees on some 80,000 hectares annually.
</P>
<P>
Central China's Hubei Province has announced a five-year plan
to close hillsides to facilitate afforestation projects and an
ambitious program to plant trees on over one million hectares.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi Province in east China plans to establish an ecological
shelterbelt system around Poyang Lake, and areas accounting for 32
percent of the province's total territory.
</P>
<P>
North China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region has vowed to
expand shelterbelt construction, and plant trees along railways
and highways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
