<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Says Cannot Stem Rising Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Ministry of
Manpower has admitted it has little power to stem the increasing
tide of unemployment in the country because it has been forced to
postpone many of its development projects.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Manpower Fahmi Idris told legislators in a hearing
on Monday that many of his ministry's planned development projects
had been postponed due to the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will be unable to reach its target of spending 50
percent of its 1998/99 fiscal year (beginning April) budget for
development projects because of the delays, he was quoted by the
Jakarta Post Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"How can the nation cope with unemployment if the economic
crisis and political turmoil continue to worsen?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that unemployment in Indonesia has shot up 100
percent from nine million in July last year to 18 million this
month.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Center for Research and Development Planning at
the ministry Yudo Swasono told legislators that he feared sporadic
looting and unrest would continue since the crisis had yet to show
signs of easing.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jakarta Post, at least three people have died
and dozens more have been injured in clashes with security forces
in recent sporadic outbreaks of rioting and looting in some areas
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Since Saturday, sporadic looting has been breaking out in East
Java province. In one incident in Bondowoso, a man was shot dead
on Sunday morning when troops tried to stop a mob from pillaging
rice mills and shops selling basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, hundreds of people looted two major chicken
farms in the Pakis district of Malang, and another hundreds of
residents from the Gondanglegi area of the city looted a warehouse
where a man allegedly storing 50 tons of rice.
</P>
<P>
Still in East Java, a crowd in Cerme district looted three
shrimp farms with impunity on Monday morning, and hundreds of
people stole timber from a teak plantation in Banyuwangi regency
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The looting in East Java has gone way too far," Regional
Military Commander Maj. Gen. Djoko Subroto said, adding that he
would not hesitate to issue a shoot-on-the-spot order to his men
if looters continued to defy the security forces.
</P>
<P>
In Luwu regency, 460 kilometers north of the South Sulawesi
provincial capital of Ujungpandang, a brawl between youths from
two villages erupted into full-blown rioting which killed two and
left 18 others injured.
</P>
<P>
A looting spree also took place Monday morning on a noodle
warehouse in Batanghari regency in Jambi province in Sumatra
island.
</P>
<P>
In the North Sumatra capital of Medan, a mob of 100 people took
advantage of the chaos caused by a public transport drivers'
strike to attack the city's luxurious Plaza Yuki Simpang Raya
shopping center on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hit by the worst economic crisis in decades, the paper said,
Indonesia has borne witness to a rising incidence of social unrest
over the past year. Earlier this month, major looting sprees broke
out in Pontianak, West Kalimantan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
