<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Gears up for Severe Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
will soon form a rescue team in anticipation of major floods
predicted to hit several regions of the country in October,
Transportation Minister Giri Suseno said.
</P>
<P>
He said he will be part of the team to be formed by
Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare and Poverty Eradication
Haryono Suyono, the Indonesian Observer reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Suseno was speaking after opening the 12th Conference of the
Regional Association V (Southwest Pacific) of the World
Meteorology Organization (WMO) in Bali Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the regional level, he said, similar task forces set up to
handle severe floods will be headed by provincial governors.
</P>
<P>
The team will provide information and early warnings to people
before floods occur. It will also take preventive measures to
reduce the severity of the expected floods, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorology and Geophysics Agency has said Indonesia will
be affected by major floods caused by the La Nina weather
phenomenon from October to December.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Suseno said the WMO conference is
strategically important to countries in the Southwest Pacific,
particularly with respect to the exchange of data among national
meteorological agencies, so that these countries could prepare for
disasters brought about by natural phenomena occurring in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the conference's organizing committee Sri Diharto
said the main program of the WMO is "World Weather Watch", which
encourages national meteorological agencies under the organization
to coordinate their meteorological observation and data processing
functions.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day conference, which commenced Monday, is attended by
57 participants from 15 countries.
</P>
<P>
One of the main topics to be discussed is the planning and
realization of a cooperation agreement between national
meteorological agencies in the Southwest Pacific. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
