<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Budget Deficit Surges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
budget deficit rose sharply to 22.6 billion pesos (526 million
U.S. dollars) in the first eight months this year, nearly double
the figure registered one month earlier, the Philippine Star
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following a surplus in July, the national government's cash
position reverted back to a deficit due to a decline in the
collection of the Bureau of Internal Revenue, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The government, whose deficit declined to 13.6 billion pesos
(316 million dollars) at the end of July this year due to a
surplus that month, acquired a deficit of 9 billion pesos (2.1
million dollars) in August.
</P>
<P>
According to some sources, the July surplus position was
questioned by an International Monetary Fund review mission that
visited the country recently.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, is reportedly "comfortable" with the
whopping deficit for the January to August period especially since
it is expecting a 40 billion pesos (930 million dollars) deficit
for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
For next year, the Philippine government expects to incur a
cash budget shortfall of at least 30 billion pesos (698 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The IMF is urging the government to come up with more concrete
revenue measures to improve its financial situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
