<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Leader Visits U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A top Chinese military
leader arrived here Monday to discuss ways to further military
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wannian, vice chairman of the Central Military Commission
of China, said at Andrews Military Air Base in a written statement
that he had come to the United States to implement the agreements
reached between Chinese and U.S. presidents, arrange further
military exchanges and promote development of bilateral
military-to-military relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited the United States last
fall and U.S. President Bill Clinton paid a return visit to China
in late June.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to build a constructive strategic relationship
between the two countries. Closer military-to-military ties are
important part of it.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to exchange military observers to
watch the other side's military exercises and enhance cooperation
in rescue operations in addition to efforts to avoid sea accidents.
</P>
<P>
"Both China and the United States are countries that carry
considerable weight and shoulder major responsibilities in the
world. A joint commitment by China and the United States to a
constructive strategic partnership based on enhanced cooperation
not only serves the fundamental interests of our two countries,
but also contributes to peace, stability and development in the
world," Zhang said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Zhang is expected to meet U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen and other government and military leaders during his stay
until Thursday in Washington to "exchange views on issues of
mutual interest."
</P>
<P>
"China attaches great importance to developing relations with
the United States. Since last fall, our two Presidents have
successfully exchanged visits and reached agreements on a wide
range of major international and bilateral issues, thus bringing
Sino-U.S. relationship to a new stage of development. As a result,
the military-to-military relations between our two countries have
also made fresh progress," Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese general will visit several military bases and watch
military exercises in the United States. His visit will last about
10 days.
</P>
<P>
Apart from meetings with U.S. government and military leaders,
"I will have extensive contacts with American men and women in
uniform. I believe that with concerted efforts by our two sides,
this visit will surely be a complete success," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Cohen is going to accord him an official welcome at
the Pentagon, which will be followed by meetings between the two
sides on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
