<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Yang Shangkun, former Chinese president and a veteran leader
of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the armed forces, died
of illness yesterday morning in Beijing. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
An obituary issued by the central authorities called Yang a
great proletarian revolutionary, statesman and strategist, a
staunch Marxist, and an outstanding leader of the Party, the state
and the people's army.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin met with Mary Robinson, United
Nations high commissioner for human rights, here yesterday. They
had a friendly talk on international cooperation for promoting,
advancing and safeguarding human rights.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China is a developing country with a population of
1.2 billion. "To develop and protect human rights, we should first
take into account our national conditions. That is to place
economic growth in priority in order to feed and clothe the
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang, China places democratic and legal
development in an important position in the process of economic
growth, and the advancement of civil and political rights for the
people through judiciary and executive measures.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- In an unprecedented internal shake-up of the judiciary,
China reshuffled a considerable number of courts and prosecutorial
offices and disciplined nearly 5,000 judges and prosecutors in the
first eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Courts had also corrected 8,110 misjudged cases by August and
prosecutors reconsidered 1,125 mishandled criminal offenses by
July.
</P>
<P>
President of the Supreme People's Court Xiao Yang and
Procurator-General of the Supreme People's Procuratorate Han
Zhubin revealed these figures yesterday when reporting to the
Civil and Judiciary Committee of the National People's Congress
(NPC) on their work in the "Intensified Educational Rectification
Movement".
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and his Irish counterpart Bertie
Ahern held talks in the Great Hall of the People yesterday in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to exchange views on a wide range of issues
of shared interest.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's township enterprises grew 15.6 percent in the first
eight months of 1998, and are in a good position to contribute 3.6
percentage points to this year's planned growth in gross domestic
product, an official from Ministry of Agriculture said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Officials with the Association for Relations Across the
Taiwan Straits (ARATS) welcome comments from some people in Taiwan
who suggest that political dialogues are needed to resolve
cross-Straits issues.
</P>
<P>
ARATS reaffirmed its position yesterday in a letter to the
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF).
</P>
<P>
-- China will unveil its first securities law at the earliest
possible date, in an effort to promote a stable and healthy
development of its fledgling securities market, an official source
said yesterday. 
</P>
