<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flowers Make Chinese People's Life More Beautiful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of Chinese people
who decorate their homes with flowers is increasing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
One indication is that flower-sales volume in China has has
been growing markedly over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
According to the China Flowers and Potted Plant Landscape
Association, 1.9 billion flowers were sold in 1997, compared with
1.1 billion in 1996; sales volume of potted flowers was over 1
billion in 1997, more than twice the figure for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Weixian, deputy secretary of the association, said, "This
reflects the increase in Chinese people's income and the
improvement in their living conditions, as well as their stronger
sense of beautifying their living environment."
</P>
<P>
China's flower industry has been developing rapidly for over
ten years. In 1984, the total acreage of flowers in the country
was 14,000 hectares, with an output value of 600 million yuan. By
the end of last year, the acreage had expanded to over 80,000
hectares, and the output value to 9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The increase in flower-planting has caused flower prices to
drop by 50 percent in the past few years, enabling more Chinese to
buy flowers.
</P>
<P>
The per capita flower consumption in Shanghai with a population
of 13 million, for example, was nearly 30 for 1997, and in
Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province, flowers are
sold at outdoor markets just like vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese flower dealers have even launched their businesses
on the Internet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
