<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remains of Carved Jade Suit Found in Ancient Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 pieces of
carved jade believed to be from a jade burial suit have been found
in a tomb dating back some 2,000 years in north China's Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archeologists say that such jade pieces, carved with
designs of the sun, the moon, dragons, flowers and birds, have
rarely been seen before in jade burial suits.
</P>
<P>
The experts say that the tomb, 30 meters long, 30 meters wide
and 5 meters high, probably belonged to a nobleman of the late
Western Han Dynasty (206 BC-24 AD).
</P>
<P>
Jade burial suits, always made with gold or silver thread, were
usually used to adorn the bodies of royalty in ancient China.
</P>
<P>
Though apparently robbed several times, the tomb still
contained bronze weapons including a crossbow devices, and sword
and arrows, in addition to the pieces of carved jade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Should not Hide Wrongdoing, Says White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The White House, in
response on Monday to calls for President Bill Clinton to abandon
legalistic denials of perjury charges, said he had already
admitted wrongdoing in his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said Clinton's admissions
should not be obscured by the work his lawyers are doing to defend
him from allegations of perjury and other misconduct in
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report on the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
"The president's lawyers have said, and many independent
observers agree, that Mr. Starr's allegations would not support a
case of perjury in a court of law," Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless the president has made clear that he does not
want the work of his lawyers to get in the way of his admission
that he had an improper relationship and he misled people to keep
it private.
</P>
<P>
"No legalisms should obscure the fact that it was wrong. He
apologized for it and he's asked for forgiveness," Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
Leading Congressional Democrats, including Senate Democratic
Leader Tom Daschle and House Democratic Leader Representative
Richard Gephardt, earlier on Monday urged Clinton to abandon
"hair-splitting" legalistic defenses of Starr's charges.
</P>
<P>
Starr's report released last Friday accused Clinton of lying to
lawyers in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit and to Starr's
investigators in denying his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's lawyers have contended that although the president
may have made misleading statements in testimony, they did not
constitute perjury and he testified truthfully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
