<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Labor Wins in One Poll, Loses in Another </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Support for the opposition
Australian Labor Party (ALP) exceeded that for the ruling
coalition in the latest poll conducted for the nation's leading
newspaper The Australian, but another poll result shows just the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
According to the results of the latest Newspoll published in
Tuesday's Australian newspaper, the ALP broke a stalemate that had
existed throughout the campaign to move two points clear.
</P>
<P>
The support for the Labor Party rose by 2.5 percentage points
to 44 percent while support for the ruling Liberal Party and
National Party coalition was up 0.5 percentage point to 42
percent, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
But another poll, to be published this week by the nation's
weekly news magazine the Bulletin, found that 44 percent of voters
backed the Liberal Party and the National Party, and only 34
percent supported Labor.
</P>
<P>
Never before during an election campaign have the polls so
widely differed, the Australian Associated Press said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Even more confusing, both are telephone polls conducted around
the same time last weekend.
</P>
<P>
According to the two polls, support for One Nation Party led by
Pauline Hanson is down in the poll average to seven points.
</P>
<P>
While the poll average shows the coalition a comfortable four
points in front, the ALP will draw comfort from the fact that the
only poll to have Labor ahead, Newspoll, is also the poll with the
best record of predicting election results.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard, who set October 3 as the federal
election date on August 30, said Friday the election would be a
"tight" one.  
</P>
</TEXT>
