<HEADLINE> Canadian Observer Injured by Anti-Tank Mine in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A vehicle carrying three
Canadian diplomatic observers hit a mine and overturned in western
Kosovo on Monday, leaving a woman interpreter injured.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Pristina news center said the incident
happened in the Drenica area south of the village of Likovac,
while the three-member team was heading for Donje Obrinje, a
village dominated by ethnic Albanian gunmen of the separatist
"Kosovo Liberation Army" (KLA).
</P>
<P>
"A mine exploded under the right rear wheel of our vehicle and
left a crater of about two meters wide and one meter deep," Gavin
Buchan, one of two Canadian observers told reporters.
</P>
<P>
John Sheahen, the other observer, said he was sure the weapon
was an anti-tank mine.
</P>
<P>
Serbian police reportedly came to their aid after the observers
called them for help; the Serbians were fired on by KLA gunmen,
police said.
</P>
<P>
Observers said they heard bursts of fires for half a hour and
were eventually evacuated by a number of armored vehicles and Serb
police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
