<HEADLINE> Spurs Reject Takeover Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Tottenham Hotspur chairman
Alan Sugar said that he has turned down a takeover bid which
would have valued the White Hart Lane club at 80 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he had received an approach from leisure
group ENIC.
</P>
<P>
ENIC, which is backed by Bahamas based billionaire Joe Lewis
and Time Warner, the U.S. media giant, owns a host of European
clubs, has a stake in Glasgow Rangers and is known to want to
extend its interests with a move into the Premiership.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Sugar has been rumoured to be keen to sell his near 40%
stake in his club for some time, but was not tempted by the price
offered by ENIC.
</P>
<P>
However City analysts believe ENIC could increase its offer to
win control of the club.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Tottenham Hotspur leapt almost 17% to 84p on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Spurs are the latest club to be linked with a takeover
following BSkyB's proposed 623m buy-out of Manchester United and
media giants Carlton Communications possible link with Double
winners Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
The latest twist in the saga comes at the end of a dramatic
week for football.
</P>
<P>
Since news of the likely BSkyB takeover broke, intense
speculation has surrounded the future of several top teams.
</P>
<P>
Millions of pounds were added to the value of clubs like Aston
Villa and Newcastle United on the London Stock Exchange on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sheffield United, has also revealed it is in preliminary talks
with a number of individuals, which might be interested in taking
a substantial stake in the club. 
</P>
</TEXT>
