<HEADLINE> Security Council to Resume Consultations on Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council is expected to resume closed-door consultations on the
situation in the war-torn Angola before its ending with a
resolution on whether to extend the mandate of the United Nations
Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA).
</P>
<P>
Hans Dahlgren, president of the 15-member Security Council made
the statement following Monday's secret consultations on Angola.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council will take a decision by Tomorrow evening
at the latest" on the situation in Angola, where the fighting is
still raging on, he said.
</P>
<P>
In his report submitted the Security Council late last week,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan proposed that the mandate of the
MONUA be extended to January 31, 1999, if the warring factions in
the southern African country have made substantial progress in
full compliance with the 1994 Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Angola is currently locked in a stalemate in the completion of
the peace process under the Lusaka Protocol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
