<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2050GMT, September 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- an armed hijacker of a Turkish passenger plane
surrendered at the airport in Trabzon province along the Black Sea
of Turkey after releasing all people on board.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency quoted General Director
of the Turkish Airlines Yusuf Bolayirli that there is no
high-ranking official among the 76 hijacked passengers and eight
crew.
</P>
<P>
The agency reported that the gunman had hijacked the
plane in protest against the Turkish government's decision to
prevent girl students from wearing headscarves in schools and
universities.
</P>
<P>
The gunman hijacked the plane on the Ankara-Istanbul flight
at 20:37 local time (17:37 GMT) soon after the aircraft took
off from Ankara Esenboga Airport. (Turkey-Hijack)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Following days of wrangling, Israeli cabinet on
Sunday night passed with a majority state budget for 1999
featuring overall spending cut but defense outlays rise.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen of the 17 ministers voted in favor of the budget
proposal, two were against and one abstained, Radio reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The review of the 1999 budget proposal, which plans a overall
cut and an increase in defense spending for the first time in 10
years, began last week, with 11 ministers being reported to have
opposed the program at the time. (Israel-Budget-Approval)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's special envoy on Afghan affairs Alaeddin
Boroujerdi on Monday called for a trial of leaders of the Afghan
Taliban militia by an international court for "racial and
religious cleansing in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Boroujerdi made
the call in a speech at Tehran University and said that the
Taliban's killing of Iranian diplomats and reporter would not be
unanswered. (Iran-Taliban-Trial)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said in
south Lebanon on Monday that Israel would continue its efforts to
conclude a security agreement with Lebanon, the Orient radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The would-be agreement will provide security for Israel's
northern villages and towns, he said during an inspection tour of
Israeli forces in its occupied south
Lebanon. (Lebanon-Israel-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The Iraqi National Assembly (parliament) passed a
resolution to sever all kinds of relations with the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) authorized to dismantle the Iraqi mass
destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issed on Monday after an emergency session, the
assembly recommended the severing of relations with the UNSCOM and
halting all its activities in Iraq in case the U.N. Security Council
does not meet the Iraqi demands. (Iraq-UNSCOM)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel successfully conducted an integrated test
of its "Arrow" missile system Monday afternoon, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The test was conducted in a military base outside Tel Aviv and
it was the first time that all three components of the defense
system -- the missile, the radar and the fire-control system --
had been involved, the radio quoted officials as
saying. (Israel-Arrow-Test) 
</P>
