<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Concludes DPRK Launches Satellite, Not Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States, backing
away from its initial assessment, concluded Monday that the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) launched a satellite
two weeks ago, but not a missile.
</P>
<P>
"We have concluded that North Korea did attempt to orbit a very
small satellite," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters. "We also have concluded the satellite failed to achieve
orbit," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Aug. 31 rocket firing was first described by U.S. officials
as a multi-stage Taepo Dong-1 missile that has a range of more
than 1,930 km and has been viewed as threatening, especially by
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the United States has tended to ignore official DPRK
statement that the Aug. 31 launch involved a satellite, although
South Korea's foreign minister said in Washington last Friday that
based on talks with U.S. experts it appeared that a satellite
launch was most probable.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the purpose of the rocket-firing is now
believed to have been a satellite launch. "Nevertheless, the North
Koreans have demonstrated in this launch a capability to deliver a
weapons payload against surface targets at... increasing ranges,
confirming the inherent capability to threaten its neighbors," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"So we regard this missile as a threat to U.S. allies, friends
and forces in the region," he said, adding the launch would be
among the topics discussed at a Monday meeting at the State
Department of U.S., Japanese and South Korean officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
