<DOCNO> XIE19980915.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Continues to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rose sharply
Monday, extending Friday's rally, with the Dow Jones industrial
average finishing 149.85 points higher at 7,945.35 after rising by
as much as 243 points.
</P>
<P>
The Dow now sits above its 1998 starting point, 7,908.25. The
blue-chip barometer is still about 1,300 points, or 14 percent,
below the July 17's high.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators also extended Friday's rally. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 20.66 to 1,029.72, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 24.05 to 1,665.69.
</P>
<P>
Advancers beat decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 709.73 million shares down
from 817.73 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 10.18 to 510.21, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 6.09 to 619.30.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.10 to 357.72.
</P>
<P>
In Asia and Europe, stock markets also rallied on some
encouraging news.
</P>
<P>
In a speech in New York Monday, President Clinton said he has
asked Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan to meet with their counterparts from other leading
nations to coordinate a strategy against the "biggest financial
challenge facing the world in a half century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
